1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:22,000
Okay, okay. Good afternoon. Today is August 15, 2013. Speaking is David Klein from the History Department at Virginia Tech.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:27,000
Also working with the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina Chapel Hill.

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:36,000
We are conducting an interview today for the Civil Rights History Project of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Behind the camera is John Bishop of Media Generation and we have the honor today of interviewing John and Jean Rosenberg.

6
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Jean is on Channel 1 and John is on Channel 2 and I just want to thank you both very much for being part of this project.

7
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Glad to be here.

8
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:00,000
And we'll start today with we're going to start with Jean and I just wanted to...

9
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:13,000
I usually start with people's family backgrounds in the belief that maybe you'll prove me wrong but that often the way that people are raised and the ideals and the influence,

10
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:22,000
you can see later what a person ends up doing and so I'm curious, I'm always curious about the family life of people as they are raised.

11
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:26,000
So if you could tell us a little bit about your backgrounds and whether you see any of those kind of...

12
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Oh, absolutely. I mean I think that's absolutely true in my observation of life too.

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:55,000
So I was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania and adopted by a transplanted New York couple and my father having been uprooted from his Presbyterian community was looking for a place to a spiritual growth and connected with the Quakers.

14
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:07,000
And subsequently we... he joined and I joined and then later my brother and my mother joined the Quaker meeting in Abington, Pennsylvania.

15
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And that led to intense exposure to social action and commitment to the idea that there's that of God in every person.

16
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:30,000
And that and also to the fact that people can arrive at decision making by consensus.

17
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:43,000
And I think that that's a very important element in my later years that was a very good background for me to be living here in Appalachia.

18
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:47,000
So I went from there, I went...

19
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:53,000
Were there particular projects or focus, social justice focus in that meeting or...?

20
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:04,000
Oh well of that meeting obviously that meeting and the Philadelphia yearly meeting were always involved in racial issues.

21
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And definitely in war concern about peace, the peace process and how to accomplish that.

22
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:27,000
So I was always involved in those... that young friends movement as growing up and it guided me to apply to Earlham College in Richmond, Indiana, which is a Quaker school.

23
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:34,000
And then I graduated there in June 1965.

24
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,000
And you were born in 1943?

25
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Well you worked in... you went to a summer work camp in Mexico.

26
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Right, sure. But yeah.

27
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
That sort of thing and your mom was on the picket line for peace, right?

28
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Right.

29
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:48,000
That's what...

30
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Witness for peace, good old women.

31
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:52,000
So let's hear a little bit.

32
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:55,000
I mean just a part and parcel of my growing up years.

33
00:03:55,000 --> 00:04:05,000
And I in my high school at Abington High School, which is a suburban Philadelphia High School, refused to take part in ARA drills,

34
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:17,000
as I felt that it was a psychology of fear and terror and that in fact in a truth hiding under your desk was not going to help you in a cold war situation.

35
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:28,000
And therefore I refused. And so I was taken to the principal's office and called a Communist Dup.

36
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:36,000
And then I was directed that when we had the drill I was to sit in front of the plate glass window so I'd be the first to be killed.

37
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000
So you know, when people do that, when they take those kinds of positions, then you are...

38
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:50,000
You know, you're even more committed to thinking about what it is you're doing and why.

39
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:57,000
And so I was able to arrange for a film called Operation Correction to go along.

40
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:02,000
This is going on and on.

41
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:11,000
But you know, I mean I arranged for that to be shown in my high school just so that people could see that there was another side to a story.

42
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:14,000
And I felt that was very important.

43
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
This is the second day in a row that Operation Correction has been mentioned.

44
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:18,000
Really?

45
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:26,000
Yeah. Where was he? He was a minister that showed her that his community got run out of town for a short while.

46
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:29,000
Well, you know, luckily I was an honor student.

47
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:40,000
So, you know, I think I got more leeway because I was able to do well on tests.

48
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:48,000
So, and you started college in 1961?

49
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:51,000
At Wilmington College. I did not go to Irland, initially.

50
00:05:51,000 --> 00:06:00,000
I went and I waited too long to apply and so I had the offer of waiting out a year and coming with an ex-class or...

51
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:08,000
And I went to Wilmington College which is in Wilmington, Ohio, which is another Quaker School.

52
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:11,000
And then I transferred in my junior year.

53
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:25,000
So, and having been raised in the family and in the community that you've been telling us about, with a lot of awareness of issues, social issues and justice issues,

54
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:30,000
how were you of other things that were happening in the country?

55
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:38,000
I was part of the civil rights movement, but were you aware of earlier traditions and what was going on?

56
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
You know, were there particular movements for you?

57
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:51,000
Well, I mean, I was very aware of the Vietnam War and the lead up to that.

58
00:06:51,000 --> 00:07:05,000
And I was one of the protesters at my at Irland, you know, that would go regularly to stand and witness against the war.

59
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:15,000
And it was, however, my friend Dorothy, we referred to as Landsberg. She was Dorothy Shelton Landsberg Landsberg, then.

60
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:22,000
I met her at Irland College and she was involved with...

61
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:26,000
Her father was an internal revenue lawyer in Washington, D.C.

62
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:39,000
And he helped get her a summer internship with John Doar in the summer of 64, where she worked very hard on the developing an index of...

63
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:49,000
from the FBI reports on clan members, which was then subsequently helpful when jury selection took place in a number of cases.

64
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:58,000
And, well, I mean, we were all... she was part of the student at, you know, political activities committee and so was I.

65
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:02,000
And then I met John Doar. That's when I met John Doar.

66
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:13,000
She invited him to speak at a convocation at Irland. And she didn't want to introduce him because she was afraid he would tease her in front of everyone.

67
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:23,000
So she got her buddy Jean to introduce him. And while we were eating together, he said, well, have you ever thought about joining me establishment?

68
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:30,000
And I said, no. And he said, why don't you do that? And why don't you give it a try?

69
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:41,000
And so since I wasn't focused on where I would be after I graduated, we had thought about going to law school, but that wasn't really a passion.

70
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:54,000
So I did, in fact, apply and was accepted as a research analyst for the Civil Rights Division, the Department of Justice in June of 65.

71
00:08:55,000 --> 00:09:00,000
And I then went on to qualify my loyalty oath and I still had the job.

72
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
And what did you say?

73
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:12,000
I've inserted in the loyalty oath that I would, in so far as my conscience would allow, I would, you know, support and defend the United States.

74
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:21,000
So they kept me anyway. And that was when I started working as a research analyst.

75
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:43,000
And went from, we worked on all kinds of cases. We worked on school desegregation cases, police brutality cases, employment cases, during the time that I was there. I left in the spring of 1970.

76
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:50,000
Okay. So let's switch over to John and then we'll bring him up to that same moment.

77
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:59,000
So John, if you could introduce yourself and a little bit about your background as well, it would be wonderful.

78
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:11,000
Well, I'm John Rosenberg. I'm Jean's husband of 46 years. She's put up with me over that period, hopefully for another maybe not 46, but a few more.

79
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:18,000
I was born in Germany October 7, 1931, a long time ago.

80
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:34,000
My father was a teacher in the Jewish school system. I say the Jewish school system. He actually, when Adolf Adolf Hitler set up a secret required the schools to be segregated so that Jewish kids were separated out.

81
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:42,000
He and another man set up the school for Jewish kids and the city was named Magdeburg, Germany.

82
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:50,000
The city then, about 300,000 people, a large industrial center, which was bombed pretty heavily during the war.

83
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:59,000
And I grew up there and then as a young child, the first day of school is a big deal.

84
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:06,000
And if I remember, you go to school, start around Easter and they give you a big conical bag with all kinds of gifts in it.

85
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:12,000
I say that because we have, there's a family picture of me holding this conical bag with our gifts on the first day of school.

86
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:23,000
But I was actually, by that point, my father's class. He was a teacher and then I also worked for the Jewish welfare agency.

87
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:43,000
He was teaching courses to people who were interested in going to Israel. He wanted to go to Israel, but my mother said, no, we are, if we leave the country, we're going to go to the United States because her mother and father and two sisters had immigrated to the country and she wasn't really interested in going to Israel.

88
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:53,000
Although he had had one sister and a brother go to Israel at an early time as into a small cooperative community.

89
00:11:53,000 --> 00:12:06,000
In any event, we lived in a building next to a synagogue. We had an apartment there because dad worked for that welfare agency and he also assisted the rabbi and the local congregation.

90
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:25,000
We were there during Kristallnacht and they bombed the synagogue. They didn't, they were somewhat careful about the synagogue because there was a hospital next door. Otherwise, as you probably know, all the other synagogues, primarily were burned down or the ones most synagogues in Germany were burned.

91
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:49,000
The way my dad was in a concentration camp for 11 days and we were fortunate enough to get out of the country. We came, we spent a year in Holland. My father started a school in this detention camp and we had no materials but he taught by the Socratic Method teaching us verbally.

92
00:12:49,000 --> 00:13:13,000
We came to this country on February 22, 1940 on pretty much the last ship. His brother and mother were on board. I'm not sure about his mother. I think both of another ship of several weeks lighter in the ship was required. It was turned around because the war started.

93
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:35,000
They didn't get out. His brother was killed. He lost the, there was another family. One of his sisters had married. The fellow was on a stock exchange who was, they were fairly well off. They had five kids in Rotterdam and that family was gone and family in Germany.

94
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:55,000
Most of his, so he lost his substantial and his mother was also killed during that period. She lived right very close to the end of the war. In fact, his brother were married during the, while he was in the concentration camp and we met his widow in Israel several years later.

95
00:13:55,000 --> 00:14:17,000
But so we came and then we, my father when we came to this country, it was very difficult to find a job. There were so many immigrants in New York. And so he learned of community in Spartanburg, SC, South Carolina and Gastonian North Carolina. They had substantial Jewish communities but no rabbi.

96
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:36,000
And so he, that's what drew him there. I mean, we always, I'm not sure which comes first. But during the week he swept floors in a textile mill and on weekends he alternated going to these two communities. And I always thought it was pretty amazing because he was writing sermons when he could hardly just still learning to speak English.

97
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:46,000
But after three years we then moved. He learned of a better position in a textile mill in Gastonia, NC or in Lowell North Carolina.

98
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:55,000
Fellow who came from our hometown who in Magdeburg, a parent who had it mill they are brought a bunch of equipment and started textile mill.

99
00:14:55,000 --> 00:15:14,000
And the idea learned went to work as an office manager if I remember right. But he basically learned the textile business and stayed as a white collar worker and was very active in the local synagogue and I grew up in town of Gastonia, NC for practical purposes. We'd been in Spartanburg, SC for three years.

100
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:29,000
So I grew up in Gastonia, NC and you know worked after school and scouting was a big part of my life. I was an eagle scout and spent summers as a counselor and went off to Duke University as a freshman.

101
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:34,000
May I ask what the racial dynamics were in Gastonia, NC at that time?

102
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:44,000
I would first tell about the fact that being a German immigrant they took away the binoculars. I just think that's an interesting caveat.

103
00:15:44,000 --> 00:16:12,000
After the war started when we were aliens, my parents weren't citizens and Gene always said the FBI or Treasury agents came to our apartment one day knocked on the door and they required they took the binoculars that my parents had and the shortwave, the radio that had a capability of getting shortwave.

104
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:27,000
But they were quite embarrassed to see that we had Franklin Delano Roosevelt's picture on the wall and you have this fairly patriotic thankful family to be in this country and they came and took this equipment away from us.

105
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:34,000
It was I think mutually embarrassed very. They eventually brought it back after the war. We got this stuff back.

106
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:46,000
But we were Gastonia, NC was a segregated society. We had black schools. We had you were living in a segregated society.

107
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:59,000
You always think back on those days the Jewish community, most of the members of that community as was true and many southern communities were pretty well off.

108
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:11,000
They had their parents and grandparents had come to these communities or come to the area of his petalers and started selling merchandise and then eventually built a retail store.

109
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:23,000
The community was well off. I'm not sure that anybody had ever seen a portrait of what we were relatively poor Jewish working family until we got there.

110
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:38,000
It was a nice community and several other people were. I think they respected my father a lot because he had such a huge knowledge of Jewish culture and could read Hebrew.

111
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:52,000
We could quote the next verse in the Torah for five books of Moses if you started him anywhere in there which was not that unusual for someone who had all that biblical background or studied in the some he had been to the seminary.

112
00:17:52,000 --> 00:18:01,000
He actually came from family with nine children in northwest Germany and one of his early teaching assignments was in my mother's hometown.

113
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:09,000
She was a young 16 year old and they got to know each other and by when she was 18 they got married.

114
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:28,000
He was working in the mill and I had some of jobs in the mill and it was as you lived as you know, every Jewish community was thankful to be there economically.

115
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:37,000
They couldn't get into the country club for many despite their wealth. Most of them were not at that point. The country clubs were segregated.

116
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:48,000
But they certainly took no major initiatives in trying to help integrate the community or call attention to the fact that this is wrong.

117
00:18:48,000 --> 00:19:01,000
I think you basically grew up with it and when you move into that system looking back, I'm sure my parents were so grateful to be there that they were. That was the last thing they had in mind.

118
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:13,000
Although my parents, my mother especially, I mean my summer job, I worked off when you're in the mill you interact with lots of black folks.

119
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:18,000
But everybody kind of knows where the lines are.

120
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:32,000
I don't know if there was any Gastonia, NC's history is sort of interesting. There are book called preachers and mill hands. They had riots in the 20s and 30s around the textile worker issue and working conditions.

121
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:39,000
But it wasn't racial. It wasn't that was not a racial issue.

122
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:53,000
So the schools were totally segregated and that's just the way life was. My mother had my mom was known to be a very friendly person. She was and didn't start work.

123
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:02,000
She decided after the kids were all gone that she wanted to be a saleswoman to do work in the local department store which she did.

124
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:13,000
But she had people coming by where they were black or white and she would interact with them and offer them bite the eat or whatever.

125
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:22,000
And I think the family in that sense, I didn't have don't recall. I don't think I had any friends in the black community.

126
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:47,000
A few years ago, not too many years ago, 10 years ago I think Gastonia, NC, the class president of the year before me or two years, promoted a joint anniversary of the classes from 1948 so that the black and white graduates would now be adults would be together.

127
00:20:47,000 --> 00:21:09,000
I think it was a one time thing. But I remember that Gaston County Gaston County is actually one of the voting rights cases. I went to the Supreme Court. I think they challenged the mechanism under which Gaston County was selected.

128
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:20,000
But from that I was a Duke in a, I went to undergraduate school at Duke. It wasn't, it was sort of between Duke and the University of North Carolina.

129
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:35,000
And there was a trustee at the time named C Park who was from Gastonia, NC. And he encouraged me to go to Duke because he thought he could secure and he did secure a tuition scholarship for me for the first four, what we hope would be four years.

130
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:48,000
Unfortunately, he died after the first year. And I was then interviewed and said, you're making too much money working in the dining room where you got chips for food or whatever. And they said, you got to have to pay your own tuition.

131
00:21:48,000 --> 00:22:00,000
Which I did and stayed in, but it was always sort of gosh. I was pretty poor. My dad was sending me 25 bucks a month or something and they took away the tuition scholarship.

132
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:12,000
But I did get, I was a chem major Duke and I in ROTC. And so I ended, we went into the United States Air Force. And I spent three years in England as an navigator.

133
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:24,000
London, very close to a lot of my colleagues had a very interesting year fly. We went, at that time it was a period of the Cold War.

134
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:36,000
So many of our exercises were on the close to the Russian border. We dropped the special forces and a very military period.

135
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:49,000
Totally contrary to what I was picketing the Pentagon. Right. Well, she was picketing the Pentagon. So after I came out of the service, I worked for a year for a chemical firm, Rohm and Haas, Philadelphia.

136
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:55,000
And I was just asking about the air force. The air force was integrated at that point. What was your experience there in terms of?

137
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:06,000
Well, I think it was integrated. And it was sort of in one of the things I relate as there was pretty much a life changing experience for me.

138
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:14,000
Because we were very close to each other, black sand whites. And we, on one of those occasions, we brought a plane back to this country.

139
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:26,000
And the radar operator was a fellow from Charleston, South Carolina named Abe Jenkins. And when we brought the plane back to Long Island, we went by way of Iceland and then Greenland.

140
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:42,000
It was a little, it was an SA-16 SA-16 SA-16 called a SA-16 SA-16, which flies at about 160 miles an hour. So if you've got a very heavy headwind, you might be moving along at 20 or 30 miles an hour over the ground, which on at least one occasion we did.

141
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:55,000
Because of the island, we were just about to run out of fuel anyway. We got back when we got to Long Island, even I had a week to go home. And we got on the train together in New York.

142
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:07,000
And we got to Washington. We were in uniform. And when we got to Washington, Abe said he would see me later. And I said, where are you going? He said, I'm going to the back of the train where the blacks are.

143
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:26,000
And I said, and he did. And I thought, this is bad. This is really wrong. And maybe I'm sure in the back of my mind, maybe somewhere along the way, I'll have a chance to do something about that, which show.

144
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:39,000
So you're right. It was a, I mean, in the sense that I ended up going to silver. I'm sure that particular incident had a lot to do with the way, I mean, it sorry, hit me in the head.

145
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:50,000
I don't know whether it was the first trip back when we were together. I went to an navigation school with many black members and it never seemed to be.

146
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:57,000
I'm going to cut just for a minute. Yeah. That mosquito. That mosquito is coming from me.

147
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:18,000
I'm going to take little breaks. It was interesting because in navigation school, my four of us lived together off base, four students and two of them from Texas and one was from New Orleans.

148
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:30,000
And it was at a time when people were we, I think, I don't think I had, I didn't have a car, but I know that one of them did and we had this Confederate Air Force sticker on there.

149
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:40,000
And it was still the institution was as an institution, but there was still a fair amount of racism and joking and that sort of thing.

150
00:25:40,000 --> 00:26:08,000
And going on and it was all part of the way you lived, but you also, I think, I think they saw that the members, the black officers who were in navigation training at that time, you know, it was their first, everybody's first experience in a major way of living together, working together and eventually having to depend on each other.

151
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:25,000
So that was just leading up to the time that we were when I went to England. And then we were, you have crew members and you're in some fairly dangerous situations and you just know for sure that the color of your skin didn't make any difference at all.

152
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:36,000
You're involved in a very difficult exercise in which they're depending on you or you're depending on them as much as you are any other anybody else.

153
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:45,000
And for you personally, I don't know whether if there are African Americans in your classes at Duke or was this really for you the first time to be in Coast Park Simulator?

154
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:52,000
It was. Duke was still a white school. Duke was still segregated. I had a Jewish quota.

155
00:26:52,000 --> 00:27:02,000
Yeah, they had a quota for Jewish, which I don't think I was aware of in the sense that, you know, we thought, well, this is the number.

156
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:12,000
But when I went to Duke, the two roommates I had were both Jewish. We weren't put there by accident. But there was a Jewish fraternity.

157
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:23,000
Did you come into each other about that? I don't know. You know, it turned out that one of them and I were lifelong friends.

158
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:29,000
The other one of them became a doctor. Norman Rosenbaum went to the University of Virginia and ended up in New England.

159
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:38,000
And he was always, Norman was much more of a loner. He played, he was from Norfolk and had played basketball. But he always went off to study on his own.

160
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:45,000
And then Marty and I ultimately joined the Jewish fraternity, which was a big, new experience for me.

161
00:27:45,000 --> 00:28:05,000
I've never been with a lot of Jews. I was president of my senior class in high school. And just one of the boys, as it were, you know, you felt you were a member of, I don't know, that the Jewishness, I never felt any real, religious discrimination.

162
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:16,000
I mean, we were always, as Gene said, she was a very good student. People, I had a younger brother who did, who was also doing well in school.

163
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:24,000
And I was involved in a lot of activities and always working after school. And, you know, so there was people I think did respect the family.

164
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:35,000
And as I say, I was president of my sophomore class and then I gave my senior class. So I lost my career thought.

165
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:50,000
I wanted to say about my history is interestingly enough when I went to Wilmington College, which is a Quaker School, they intentionally assigned me a black roommate

166
00:28:50,000 --> 00:29:00,000
because they didn't know how the other gals on my hall would respond to being integrated in 61.

167
00:29:00,000 --> 00:29:12,000
So I got the black roommate from the Bronx and we've been lifelong friends. But it's interesting, you know, I mean, because I was a Quaker.

168
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:19,000
You know, it wasn't, you know, just because you go to a Quaker School there few and far between usually.

169
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:34,000
And she has been well. And so the three of us, Marty, this other third, the two roommates, Marty, Sak and I, he recently passed away. He was a lawyer in Jacksonville.

170
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:44,000
And he was, and we became very, very close. As I say, we both joined the fraternity and the third roommate didn't.

171
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:55,000
He was, instead independent on pretty much on his own and so Marty and I, but you had this Jewish fraternity on campus at Duke, which at that time was only Jewish.

172
00:29:55,000 --> 00:30:09,000
And after my second year, I was a delegate to a national convention in which the charter was changed to allow non-Jewish members, although it's still primarily a Jewish fraternity, I think.

173
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:18,000
But it did expose me to a whole new system. I mean, I, this, it was very helpful to, it was nice. These were pretty close.

174
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:29,000
There were very few Jewish women on the, these campus, but they were also integrated. So there was a conscious effort by the administration at that time to keep the number of students down.

175
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:37,000
Of course, today it's, there's, there's multi-national, multi-cultural, multi-religious, a very, very fine institution.

176
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:52,000
But I then went to the, after I worked for the chemical company for a year, I was thinking I wanted to do something that might be a little more useful and maybe use my brain a little bit and decide to go to the, to law school.

177
00:30:52,000 --> 00:31:03,000
And then whether I really figured out already that I was going to be on the civil rights division, I'm not sure.

178
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:21,000
I, I, Jewish had a fairly small, he was a very Jewish chambers who then was number one in our became number one in our class had a fairly small circle of non of white friends socially or to the extent that he was going to spend any time.

179
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:33,000
And he spent any time not studying. So we did become friendly during those, those years at Chapel Hill and kind of kept up with each other over the years.

180
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:49,000
I was kept up sort of with his great, his great career. And he would, we would exchange letters. And once we'll always see each other at, you know, at conferences and he'd send a little money to Appalred when I was over here.

181
00:31:49,000 --> 00:32:17,000
So from the, so after I finished law school, I was pretty determined to be in the civil rights division. And that's, I actually spent the first month and a half in the Antitrust Division waiting to get an interview with John Doar, who at that time was going down to the University of Mississippi every week too, because it was the time of getting James Meredith into Ole Miss.

182
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:26,000
And so after I interviewed with John, there were only eight or nine lawyers at that time in the division. Then I was delighted to start.

183
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:32,000
So why civil rights? And you said early on in your locker room, you saw an interest there. What was it?

184
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:46,000
Well, I mean, I think it was a combination of having been born in Germany and seeing and thinking about the hall of this Holocaust history of ours and the terrible genocide that went subject to the history of the history of the whole world.

185
00:32:46,000 --> 00:33:08,000
And then seeing that the Jewish people were, throughout Europe were subjected to. And then seeing really in having been in the service with people who were black and thinking that this is a caste system is wrong in this country, being very proud of this country.

186
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:18,000
And I'm still, I think it's the greatest place to find this country in the world. And there's just some things that we need to keep working on to make it better.

187
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:23,000
And I feel I felt that this was a place I could make a contribution.

188
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:29,000
I thought that maybe as a southerner to some extent communication wise, it's a little easier.

189
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:58,000
I don't know that I'd hoped to change any of how many people I've changed whose mind I would change. But it just seemed that the division, which was representing the United States in these cases, and that we would, that you have the force of the country behind you and that it was going to be difficult work and challenging work that was just kind of getting underway.

190
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:27,000
The division was created just 1957. And the, really didn't have very much authority to do very much itself. And the lawyers who had been working sort of as civil rights division lawyers have been sitting at their desks in Washington and were kind of reviewing papers and didn't do it very much until John Doerr came in 1960 with six months to go and Eisenhower administration and realize what you've got to do is go to the south and talk to the people who are having the problems.

191
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:46,000
And try to do something. And that was he being a trial lawyer. He said you got to go find out what the facts are. And so he was working on those, he was quite a heroic. I thought for him to take this job was six months to go. He got a call and from the eye, nobody else was willing to do it.

192
00:34:46,000 --> 00:35:05,000
And so he was actually working on one of these cases in Louisiana where a cotton farmer had registered to vote and the cotton ginners then conspired to refuse to gin as cotton because he's got name was Charles Atlas the same as the body builder.

193
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:22,000
And so the story goes if Robert F. Kennedy would become attorney general was reviewing the pleading in the affidavits in those cases and saw and had talked with John and realized that this was really a very special person who could get some things done.

194
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:35,000
I think there is a little more to it. He actually had a conversation about where things were and John explained to him by that time during after he was sort of in charge during the transition from one administration to the next.

195
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:49,000
And so Robert F. Kennedy asked John to stay on and then he did and eventually became also assistant attorney general but he was in charge of the trial work and he taught us basically his system of trying cases.

196
00:35:49,000 --> 00:36:03,000
So anyway, we can talk if you want to go back to Gene or how would you want to go back and forth. I just want to follow up on that. How closely did the attorney general and the division work?

197
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:32,000
Oh, very much so. I mean, I think the attorney general Robert F. Kennedy at that point was the boss and he he but he clearly wanted us to when I think the mission of the division and at that time in 1962 was really from a legal standpoint to challenge the voting system of voting discrimination against blacks throughout the South.

198
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:42,000
Now, other things happened and that was like James Meredith couldn't anticipate the timing of when he was going to go to Ole Miss in 1962.

199
00:36:42,000 --> 00:37:01,000
And so protecting him became an issue that took considerable division time. Lawyers were spending the or my I don't know, I gave his name Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort who is another lawyer who's in Washington who actually tried one of the big.

200
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:18,000
Colmining cases here a few years ago and wrote a book called the Buffalo Creek disaster. Gerald while I was waiting to see John, John would initially spend all his time with Meredith.

201
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:33,000
I have a really nice picture in him and I can get a McChain Marshall McChain and John with James Meredith being confronted by Lt. Gov. Paul B. Johnson Jr when they weren't going to admit him.

202
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:46,000
We might want to put in here. No, it's not when here it's up on my wall and the other room. I have to bring it down.

203
00:37:46,000 --> 00:38:04,000
But after reconstruction, blacks were basically prohibited from voting. I mean they wiped the rolls clean in most of these counties. In these rural counties, Mississippi and Alabama, I was assigned.

204
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:22,000
Initially I spent a short amount of time in Georgia. There had been a series of church burnings and I mean this efforts to protest, the failure to let people register to vote were going on all over in these various states.

205
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:49,000
We were assigned geographically and the first few months I was in Georgia working with a lawyer named Gerald "Jerry" Heilbron who had practiced in Fort Smith Arkansas for many years was one of the few private attorneys who actually, few lawyers who were private attorneys but who, when the racial issues started coming up, was viewed as a liberal and then basically lost all his business and Burke Marshall heard about it.

206
00:38:49,000 --> 00:39:02,000
They connected and he came up and spent some time eventually went to the community relations service. Jerry was sort of a glad handler but a very liberal and is thinking and wanted to do something about racial discrimination.

207
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:19,000
So I worked with Jerry for a little while and then we actually one of our very first cases with not a very good outcome. Deputy Sheriff in Sassar, Georgia, which is near America and that very difficult area, you know the area.

208
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:31,000
There were three or four black students who had gone from door to door to register people to vote and he chased them out of town with a pistol.

209
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:55,000
And so we filed a criminal information and we had a trial in federal court and we need to move stuff. Anyway, the jury wasn't out very long but it was my first case to put on some witnesses and...

210
00:39:55,000 --> 00:40:01,000
How difficult was to get with it?

211
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:02,000
And I'm...

212
00:40:02,000 --> 00:40:04,000
Van Hoffman.

213
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:06,000
Van Hoffman, post.

214
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:08,000
Yes, I remember.

215
00:40:08,000 --> 00:40:12,000
I was always dodging him.

216
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,000
Okay.

217
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:16,000
No, I'm not going to tell you that.

218
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:20,000
Well, okay.

219
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:23,000
So...

220
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:26,000
Oh, you were asking, we were talking about the...

221
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:37,000
This was my first experience in a federal criminal prosecution with the Deputy Sheriff. The jury wasn't out terribly long.

222
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:43,000
That's right. I was just about to ask how difficult it was to find people willing to testify.

223
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:49,000
In this case, the major witnesses were these black students who had been affected.

224
00:40:49,000 --> 00:41:04,000
And interesting sidelight, although I always thought a lot of Gerald "Jerry" Heilbron was that he had... he was late getting there. I think a plane was late.

225
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:13,000
So the judge wanted to start the case. So I actually examined the witnesses.

226
00:41:13,000 --> 00:41:21,000
And the early witnesses, before we got to the cross-examination of the deputy, which was after the jury was going to do it.

227
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:27,000
But I was calling these black students by their last names, Mr. Mrs. Mrs. Mrs.

228
00:41:27,000 --> 00:41:35,000
So I could see from looking around, this was people who thought that was pretty unusual.

229
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:46,000
And I'm not sure that even Jerry agreed with it a little later. I don't recall later whether he in his summation referred to them by their first names.

230
00:41:46,000 --> 00:42:01,000
He was still of the view, I think, that we could persuade southerners to comply, because even coming from his community in Fort Smith, I think he felt bad about leaving it, you know, you kind of...

231
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:18,000
That so he was still trying to sort of... well, if we're going to be a little more southerner about the way we... if we're more... if they'll understand us, maybe we can make things happen in a consensual way, as the Quakers would say.

232
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:24,000
I think the clan wasn't about to do that, and many others weren't about to do it.

233
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:33,000
But then I was transferred over to Mississippi towards the end of 1962 in the beginning of 1963.

234
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:41,000
But the answer to your question is, I think... well, it was in that case, the three black students were willing to testify.

235
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:45,000
I think it was always took a lot of courage.

236
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:47,000
Were they local? Were they coming up?

237
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:58,000
They were local. These three students that had been chased away, I think, were from another community, because he chased them out of town.

238
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:08,000
I can't remember the details of it, but they were... I think all three of them were black, and I think they'd been recruited by SNCC or one of the groups from Albany.

239
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:15,000
They may have been part of the Albany. There was a large movement in Albany, and I went to Albany several times during...

240
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:23,000
I'm just vague on that memory, because I spent a little time there, but CB King was administered...

241
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:29,000
I had spoken... had gone to and met with several times, and trying to...

242
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:41,000
What we were trying to do was be prepared and to get information back to the Attorney General's office or the Civil Rights Division about what was happening in these communities.

243
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:50,000
We didn't have any success. Really, I'm in the Georgia Church burnings. I think those were among the first things that were events, and they were at night.

244
00:43:50,000 --> 00:44:03,000
Those witnesses that you would have had to have some way into the white community or into the clan or whoever did those shootings and burnings.

245
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:15,000
We got better at it, I think, as time went on. The FBI got better with it as time went on after the Civil Rights workers were murdered, especially.

246
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:22,000
Then I moved over to the Mississippi section.

247
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:32,000
How did monitoring work? Blacks should have been allowed to register to vote, but it often had problems. How were those things monitored?

248
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:57,000
Initially, when the early first efforts to register in most of these counties, the only people who were registered was the funeral director, maybe one or two teachers, people who were sort of up to the little who were well off.

249
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:17,000
But then, SNCC, the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee and Southern Christian Leadership Conference, primarily SNCC, decided that they wanted to start a major effort in about 1961 before I came to the division.

250
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:29,000
Bob Moses was the person who was given charge of Mississippi. Even before I came, he had been beaten in a mid-county at one point.

251
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:40,000
The Civil Rights Division brought one of their first cases to stop. They were going to prosecute Bob for resisting arrest or interfering with a police officer.

252
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:55,000
Normally, a federal court does not get involved in state criminal cases. It wouldn't stop something like that because the old law was that you let you appeal a criminal case. You don't interfere with the state.

253
00:45:55,000 --> 00:46:02,000
But that was one of the first cases that the division brought to stop the police officers to stop that prosecution from going forward.

254
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:12,000
So, Bob Moses then came to Greenwood, MS and moved this, they started a major initiative in the Leflore County, MS County to get people to register.

255
00:46:12,000 --> 00:46:28,000
He and seven or eight other SNCC members who were encouraging people to go up and register were arrested and put in jail.

256
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:44,000
The division filed a lawsuit against the state of the Leflore County, MS County officials for their interference with these efforts to register people to vote under federal law.

257
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:54,000
One of my first trips to Greenwood, MS was there was a negotiated settlement which John and some officials carried out.

258
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:03,000
Remember going to the police station and getting those people out at getting Bob in a group of people out of jail.

259
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:12,000
It was a very courageous thing for any individual to go register who was black.

260
00:47:12,000 --> 00:47:21,000
I mean, they were likely to lose their job. They were people knew who they were, especially in the more, even the more rural counties.

261
00:47:21,000 --> 00:47:29,000
But in Mississippi, I think there's a picture here of a group going up to the Greenwood, MS steps if you're, if you wanted to see it.

262
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:32,000
I don't know whether it tells you anything more.

263
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:45,000
But these local officials were going to arrest, were going to do everything they could to, I don't know if the cameras still rolling out.

264
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:52,000
I showed it to you a while ago here.

265
00:47:52,000 --> 00:48:14,000
I think this is a picture of blacks after, I think after they let the SNK kids out of jail, they came up, they were not going to interfere with doing all of it.

266
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:21,000
I'm not exactly on focus here.

267
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:36,000
Well, basically what we would do would be to try to find, we would go to these counties, locate the leaders in the community, and try to identify those blacks who had gone to register or were black.

268
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:43,000
Often times they'd go up there and they'd say, you've got to see the registrar himself or herself.

269
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:52,000
She's gone. When will she be back? Well, they'd leave work and they'd try maybe one or two more times and that was it.

270
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:59,000
The truth was they'd register people over the phone if they were white or if they were black.

271
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:11,000
They'd try maybe one or two more times and that was it. The truth was they'd register people over the phone if they were white or as John used to say if they'd lived and breathed, you could vote.

272
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:14,000
But if you were black, you were out.

273
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:17,000
Would they apply literacy tests or the thing?

274
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:31,000
Well, that was the ones who got there who were able to get in, were then given a section of the Constitution that they had to be able to read and write and interpret.

275
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:42,000
So the whole, all this litigation in all these states before federal judges basically involved the administration of the literacy test.

276
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:55,000
And we produced records that we would produce, we'd have the FBI go out, well, with the FBI then and we would find the people if we could who would attempt to register or were black.

277
00:49:55,000 --> 00:50:08,000
Then we'd get the FBI to go with us into a registrar's office and we would photograph or the FBI would photograph under our supervision all the voting records in that office.

278
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:26,000
Then we would take them back to Washington and you could see on these records some of these people couldn't write at all that they were, we would try to identify those that were clearly illiterate or people you would see that numbers of people gave the same interpretation.

279
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:37,000
There's a provision in almost every constitution that says you can't, that there shall be no imprisonment for debt.

280
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:44,000
You can't put a prisoner well, they would say you can't put somebody in for dying death.

281
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:51,000
I mean there would be all sorts of totally incomprehensible interpretations by white people.

282
00:50:51,000 --> 00:51:02,000
There would be blanks. They would be, there would be a requirement under the citizenship test that you sign your name in a certain place or something.

283
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:11,000
Which they would not require white people to do. I mean it was just totally off.

284
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:31,000
So the first major case in which this was stopped basically was in front of Judge Johnson and Montgomery, Alabama, in the Macon County, Alabama and Judge Johnson ruled that you had to apply,

285
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:43,000
they had to apply the same standards to blacks that they did for whites. So if you didn't require a white person interpret the constitution or correctly you're no longer going to have to do it.

286
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:52,000
It was called the freezing principle that the standard is frozen where it is applied to whites. Now not all the other judges.

287
00:51:52,000 --> 00:52:12,000
Judge Johnson was really a beacon he stood by. He was probably the only federal judge for many years at the trial level. They had to protect him for these very fair, very strong orders that he issued in all these cases.

288
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:25,000
But in Mississippi we had Judge W. Harold Cox in Jackson on and most of the cases in the Southern District. Judge W. Harold Cox had been Judge Senator James O. Eastland's roommate I think.

289
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:40,000
He was an avowed segregationist and he would just put all sorts of roadblocks in your way. And we would try to get a motion heard to photograph records who would took two or three years to litigate that motion.

290
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:53,000
I would say the statute didn't mean what it said. So those cases proceeded very slowly and he would we would have to peel every order and contrary to Judge Johnson.

291
00:52:53,000 --> 00:53:03,000
Judge Johnson he might say, oh this is discrimination against this person. I'm going to order you register these five people. I mean it just went.

292
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:22,000
So then we also filed the government civil rights division under with John and there were two or three other sectional leaders Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort who was from had gone to California to law school who was probably 80% blind.

293
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:43,000
I don't know the person. He had a monocular. He was a remarkable person, remarkable lawyer that we could talk about for a long time and Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort who ran the Mississippi section who came from Texas and fell in named Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort who was in charge of Louisiana.

294
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:54,000
Anyway, David came up with the theory that we should sue the state of Louisiana across the board and we sued. We brought.

295
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:59,000
The interuptial seconds. So within the division you had regional.

296
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:19,000
Right, we were all assigned. We were all geographical. So David, yeah initially Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort had Mississippi and what other places we were me. I think initially just had Mississippi and David had Louisiana and I was trying to who was Alabama?

297
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:32,000
See Frank had Alabama when I was in the Frank would I guess Frank had Alabama and Dave Norman had Louisiana. Those were the three and then it was Georgia and I worked for Dave. This worked for Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort and Mississippi.

298
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:45,000
And so then he assigned us by counties. So I was responsible for Leflore County, MS County and Greenwood, MS and then ended up also with Jackson and several other counties in Mississippi.

299
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:57,000
We would I mean we couldn't possibly do everything but like in Greenwood, MS at a voting case to a public and after the Civil Rights Act of 64 several public accommodation cases.

300
00:54:57,000 --> 00:55:07,000
And police brutality cases. There was the yeah and we can talk about the cases. That's where met where the fellow shot men and grivers are from.

301
00:55:07,000 --> 00:55:11,000
How many attorneys and researchers were in the division? How large was the division?

302
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:16,000
When I came I think there were 10 lawyers or 12.

303
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:31,000
For everything for the country. And now but it got larger as we grew when we had our seconds when our reasons for rights division reunion last year there were 400.

304
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:40,000
Now they have many more areas of responsibility but we did grow I think in Mississippi.

305
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:54,000
I mean it probably doubled or tripled while we were there. The joke was when you asked me about Robert F. Kennedy initially and he asked John Dore and Burke what the plan was early on after his office.

306
00:55:54,000 --> 00:56:09,000
He said we want to the plan was we want to file one action in a significant county in every state for example. He said well we have to do we can't we've got to do more than that or one in each judicial district.

