422
01:31:51,000 --> 01:32:05,000
So we were very worried about this judge before we were going to try this case. So we got to the trial and Gene and Dorothy had been watching these ballot boxes in the Sheriff's office.

423
01:32:05,000 --> 01:32:12,000
And you were looking at ballots. Yeah I'm sorry, you were counting ballots.

424
01:32:12,000 --> 01:32:15,000
We were doing it all. So...

425
01:32:15,000 --> 01:32:18,000
Day after day, I mean thousands.

426
01:32:18,000 --> 01:32:21,000
Yeah, I mean maybe they were the 17th.

427
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:33,000
Observed by Sheriff Sheriff Jim Clark's deputies who were trying to romance us and we liked to go to a crant clan rally and all this.

428
01:32:33,000 --> 01:32:37,000
You know you're scared, you don't know what's going to happen or what they're going to...

429
01:32:37,000 --> 01:32:46,000
And one of them gave Dorothy's, she still has Never" segregationist button. I was there, this guy's name was Buck. This big deputy chair of the kept trying to put the mic on Gene.

430
01:32:46,000 --> 01:32:54,000
I went, we went into this little tiny room where all the ballots were. Well we put...

431
01:32:54,000 --> 01:32:56,000
It's a button, it says never.

432
01:32:56,000 --> 01:33:00,000
You know, the segregation button says never.

433
01:33:00,000 --> 01:33:03,000
You thought that would win you over.

434
01:33:03,000 --> 01:33:06,000
Of course, I don't know who knows what's going on.

435
01:33:06,000 --> 01:33:13,000
Well Dorothy had it, I think he just thought this will give you a token of our affection because they like these two women who...

436
01:33:13,000 --> 01:33:15,000
There's well, they've met that for a while.

437
01:33:15,000 --> 01:33:19,000
Yeah, see, there's a bumper sticker.

438
01:33:19,000 --> 01:33:24,000
That was in Bogalusa, LA but it was all over the South. Never.

439
01:33:24,000 --> 01:33:28,000
I think it might have been Wallace's.

440
01:33:29,000 --> 01:33:30,000
But...

441
01:33:30,000 --> 01:33:32,000
Okay, thanks.

442
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:35,000
So the night...

443
01:33:35,000 --> 01:33:38,000
Well we were getting all this proof together.

444
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:45,000
The night before John comes in and says, well John, you should put this case on, Carc and this John.

445
01:33:45,000 --> 01:33:46,000
So I did.

446
01:33:46,000 --> 01:33:52,000
So we had this trial for several days in front of Judge Thomas and we had federal observers.

447
01:33:52,000 --> 01:33:57,000
At one point I wondered whether we thought we might have to put Gene on the stand but we didn't.

448
01:33:58,000 --> 01:34:07,000
And to make a long story short, we had federal observers who had watched these various, the Countings and had been at the polls.

449
01:34:07,000 --> 01:34:13,000
There were several hundred observers in Sheriff Sheriff Jim Clark that day at every polling place.

450
01:34:13,000 --> 01:34:19,000
I mean they were really worried this way we were going to make sure as much as we could that this election would go right.

451
01:34:19,000 --> 01:34:21,000
Because this was the first one.

452
01:34:21,000 --> 01:34:24,000
This was the first one. It was the primary in Sheriff Sheriff Jim Clark.

453
01:34:24,000 --> 01:34:31,000
So, Judge Thomas, we filed our briefs and Judge Thomas said there was nothing.

454
01:34:31,000 --> 01:34:36,000
He saw nothing. No irregularities. Only minor irregularities if there were any.

455
01:34:36,000 --> 01:34:44,000
And you shouldn't deprive the voter of the right to have his vote or her vote counted.

456
01:34:44,000 --> 01:34:49,000
Even because of maybe some minor irregularity by an election official.

457
01:34:49,000 --> 01:35:02,000
And though he ordered the votes to be counted and said there was actually an exception if the election officials found one or two ballots that were, if there was something wrong, they could discard those ballots but he had to find them.

458
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:06,000
But they didn't. So he ordered them. This was too much for him.

459
01:35:06,000 --> 01:35:17,000
The right to vote was very important. Even for this Judge who would let held on with, kept the school system segregated for a long long time.

460
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:21,000
So that was a big win. That was the first one on the voting rights case.

461
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:33,000
Now you remember probably back to 64. There was after the March not 64 but the March from Selma to Montgomery March.

462
01:35:33,000 --> 01:35:41,000
You had this Viola Viola Liuzzo situation who had, she had come down from...

463
01:35:41,000 --> 01:35:47,000
Or Ohio from somewhere near Detroit as a person of conscience who wanted to help.

464
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:52,000
And she and this young black man were taking driving.

465
01:35:52,000 --> 01:36:01,000
She was going to give a ride back to somebody to Montgomery and the clan, of course, shot and killed her that day.

466
01:36:01,000 --> 01:36:07,000
And there were several other incidents of violence around the March that happened.

467
01:36:07,000 --> 01:36:15,000
I mean the whole, the injunction, again, the government went to Johnson for an injunction to protect the marchers.

468
01:36:15,000 --> 01:36:24,000
I think the message is, I think, that the legal system, the judges, the work that the division did, was pretty substantial.

469
01:36:24,000 --> 01:36:29,000
I mean, this was a significant case, the Sheriff Sheriff Jim Clark case.

470
01:36:29,000 --> 01:36:41,000
And the whole effort to get the voting rights act of 65, the principles of that act, came out of those earlier cases I was describing to you, the freezing principle,

471
01:36:41,000 --> 01:36:47,000
the notion that you can't use a literacy test to pry somebody the right to vote.

472
01:36:47,000 --> 01:36:58,000
Now the Supreme Court this year recently turned some of that upside down, saying that everything is okay today.

473
01:36:58,000 --> 01:37:05,000
Even though there was all this testimony during the congressional hearings that said there was plenty of reason to keep the act going.

474
01:37:05,000 --> 01:37:13,000
So what was your response to that, to that recent ruling given your experience, both of you given your experience then?

475
01:37:13,000 --> 01:37:18,000
Well, I mean, I think the minority is right. I think Justice Ginsburg is right.

476
01:37:18,000 --> 01:37:22,000
I think they should have, they shouldn't have decided the case that way.

477
01:37:22,000 --> 01:37:33,000
And we heard Hillary Clinton at the American Bar Association spend a substantial amount of her time saying we've got to do something to turn that case around.

478
01:37:33,000 --> 01:37:49,000
Now whether it's congressional work or lawsuits that are going to be filed in some of the cases, you saw in a number of these states that they immediately started coming out with voter ID laws or other kinds of statutes laws that are obviously intended to turn the clock back.

479
01:37:49,000 --> 01:37:55,000
And make it more difficult for people, minorities to register to vote, that kind of thing.

480
01:37:55,000 --> 01:38:08,000
So I think it was quite, I'm sorry that I feel bad. I feel bad. I mean, I think the court, the decisions wrong, but you got, I don't agree with Bush v. Gore either, but that's our system.

481
01:38:08,000 --> 01:38:13,000
And we don't go into the streets. We start working on trying to change it.

482
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:27,000
We did interviews in Boglosa with the Robert "Bob" Hicks and all. They were doing testing of the Civil Rights Act. Were you involved in any of that? Or was that?

483
01:38:27,000 --> 01:38:52,000
Well, I'd have to go, they were doing testing of at restaurants and public accommodations and that sort of thing. Well, this paper, these pictures, well, you did the never one, one of these pictures is these folks were picketing and he's getting doused by the local barber.

484
01:38:52,000 --> 01:39:03,000
And this picture of, this is James Farmer leading the March.

485
01:39:03,000 --> 01:39:21,000
I hadn't remembered the Robert "Bob" Hicks, but I guess that's, they were leading the March of local blacks who were trying to

486
01:39:21,000 --> 01:39:32,000
support the testers and to get these stores to comply and employers to comply.

487
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:42,000
This is a similar view except it has two lawyers. One of them is Lou Couter and the other is John Rosenberg when we were at that March.

488
01:39:42,000 --> 01:39:53,000
Often the Civil Rights Division lawyers were the buffer between the police and the demonstrators and this, it was a, uh, uh.

489
01:39:53,000 --> 01:39:56,000
And why, why was that?

490
01:39:56,000 --> 01:40:09,000
I mean, you marched purposely for that reason. No, I went, why were we here? No, we weren't really, I guess we were there to kind of we were observing.

491
01:40:09,000 --> 01:40:25,000
So, which we did a lot of with the observing or interviewing so that we could gather information. I, that was the, I was saying I spent about a month in Boca-Lusa helping to put this case together.

492
01:40:25,000 --> 01:40:40,000
A lot of it was FBI work, but there were just a series of incidents directed against local blacks who were, as you say, either testing or trying to get stores and restaurants to comply.

493
01:40:40,000 --> 01:40:53,000
And, um, it seemed to me one of the incidents involved a very liberal senator from Arkansas Brooks Hayes who was supposed to come and give a talk.

494
01:40:53,000 --> 01:41:03,000
Eventually didn't, and there were the, the clan came out with a bunch of threats and leaflets and he decided he wouldn't come. He was afraid.

495
01:41:03,000 --> 01:41:11,000
But so, core organized a protest march that was fairly large.

496
01:41:11,000 --> 01:41:24,000
Um, and, uh, this, it was really, we were observing these marches. Blue was there for a while. I don't, I didn't remember. I don't know how long he was there, but I spent almost a month together.

497
01:41:24,000 --> 01:41:43,000
And then at the end, I went to see, uh, we put the case together and went to Judge John Judge John Minor Wisdom. I always tell people when you, when you go to law school, you're one of your early courses is called equity or remedy.

498
01:41:43,000 --> 01:42:04,000
And the history of equity is that, um, it was a change in the law from just being able to get damages and to, to the, the courts with, the equity courts had a chancellor who could stop bad behavior.

499
01:42:04,000 --> 01:42:18,000
You could, and if you needed to writ, you supposedly could go, this goes historically, you could go see the chancellor even in his night shirt so that you could get a relief.

500
01:42:18,000 --> 01:42:29,000
And that, so in my clan case, I always remember I went at that time, the fifth circuit had its main offices in, was in New Orleans and the old fish and wildlife building.

501
01:42:29,000 --> 01:42:40,000
And at the time, I don't think there was even a good air conditioning system. So I went looking for a Judge John Judge John Minor Wisdom, Judge John Minor Wisdom on a Saturday. It was hotter than blazes.

502
01:42:40,000 --> 01:42:59,000
I finally found Judge John Judge John Minor Wisdom in the back in his office and he was sitting there in his undershirt. And so I went to Judge John Judge John Minor Wisdom and said, Your Honor, we have this petition, we have to get a preliminary injunction against the plan for, to stop these activities.

503
01:42:59,000 --> 01:43:18,000
I mean, we would need a trial, but in order to get things underway, you have to get him to sign this order. And so he did, and so I always think that I went to see some people saw the chancellor in, in his night shirt, I got an injunction from Judge John Judge John Minor Wisdom in his, in his undershirt.

504
01:43:18,000 --> 01:43:31,000
He was hotter than he was perspiring. I later got an award in his name, but I never, and I, and he escaped before I could get him to sign the program.

505
01:43:31,000 --> 01:43:34,000
But keep looking at, I know it's in there.

506
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:37,000
What are you looking for? I thought the hose picture from both sides.

507
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:45,000
Oh, yeah, I'm sure it's here. There were, there are a couple of these pictures that, and I think this is a different picture of the March.

508
01:43:45,000 --> 01:43:47,000
That's the Edmund Pennis Bridge.

509
01:43:47,000 --> 01:43:54,000
So, Johnny, you weren't, you weren't worried about your safety too often between, did you worry about him or about yourself?

510
01:43:54,000 --> 01:44:00,000
Well, we were not, you know, at that time I wasn't married to him.

511
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:07,000
What you like? So, I did like him. Yeah, I did like him.

512
01:44:07,000 --> 01:44:13,000
There were time, there it is. There were times when I was really frightened.

513
01:44:13,000 --> 01:44:26,000
And we've had some pretty unpleasant incidents, because of course I was in primarily in Alabama in those early years, and we never knew if we needed to seek,

514
01:44:26,000 --> 01:44:32,000
go into a restaurant, what would happen? You know, our water would get spit in and that stuff.

515
01:44:32,000 --> 01:44:37,000
We would get that kind of treatment. And you never knew whether that was going to escalate.

516
01:44:37,000 --> 01:44:42,000
I mean, now when you look back you think, oh, how safe we were, but we didn't feel that safe.

517
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:55,000
And I remember once, we worked very hard, and on the Meredith March, I was the traveling connector between the attorneys who were in the field.

518
01:44:55,000 --> 01:45:02,000
With the March, walking with the marchers and the attorney general.

519
01:45:02,000 --> 01:45:06,000
And they would report to me and I would report to him.

520
01:45:06,000 --> 01:45:15,000
And we worked until like 10 and 11 at clock at night, and I remember one of the attorneys and I decided we'd just take a walk.

521
01:45:15,000 --> 01:45:20,000
I was in Yazoo City, Mississippi, and we'd just take a walk around the block.

522
01:45:20,000 --> 01:45:29,000
And we got about a quarter of a way around the block, and all of a sudden this car pulls up behind us, screeching,

523
01:45:29,000 --> 01:45:42,000
and people jump out and they start following us. And George, who is from Mississippi, said, now, Gene, just keep looking straight ahead and keep on walking.

524
01:45:42,000 --> 01:45:51,000
And I remember when you're frightened like that, your feet feel like you're walking through mud.

525
01:45:51,000 --> 01:45:57,000
But we made it back to the hotel and nothing happened. But we didn't know.

526
01:45:57,000 --> 01:46:01,000
And so we felt very vulnerable sometimes.

527
01:46:01,000 --> 01:46:11,000
I thought you were going to remember after the lowest race, one of the first black secretary in Selmo.

528
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:20,000
In our office, we opened an office, the Civil Rights Division, in his later years, started opening out of few offices outside of Washington.

529
01:46:20,000 --> 01:46:31,000
And the first one was in Selma, Alabama. Later there was one in New Orleans, and the lawyer who's in charge of the office who lived there, in Selmo was Chad Quaintance.

530
01:46:31,000 --> 01:46:50,000
He's in Minneapolis, and after he left the division, he went to a large law firm in Minneapolis, and then he semi-retired and went to Divinity School, and never became a minister, but he's been teaching religion.

531
01:46:50,000 --> 01:46:56,000
He taught religion at Hanover College, and said some eyesight problems, but they are.

532
01:46:56,000 --> 01:47:05,000
And so he's one of the folks who spoke on that particular event and talked about it, one of his Alabama cases.

533
01:47:05,000 --> 01:47:17,000
But he also mentioned Blowest Reese, who is this secretary in Selmo, now many years later, of course, but she's still living.

534
01:47:17,000 --> 01:47:30,000
But we had worked together very, very hard preparing a big massive school desegregation case, and making in Alabama.

535
01:47:30,000 --> 01:47:32,000
What did you want to do?

536
01:47:32,000 --> 01:47:39,000
No, it was the league against making it, and that's when we were up for three days and nights, straight around the clock.

537
01:47:39,000 --> 01:47:47,000
And she was a small town, she came from Selmo, we were in Montgomery, and she was my roommate.

538
01:47:47,000 --> 01:48:06,000
And after the third day, when it was finished, we went, and now it had big meal, and then we went back to the motel room, and she had run out of her epilepsy.

539
01:48:06,000 --> 01:48:27,000
But she didn't know how, you know, I now know living here in a rural setting that you don't necessarily think first about calling back to the pharmacy, or I mean, I can understand why she didn't try to get a refill.

540
01:48:27,000 --> 01:48:33,000
But she had a grandmaw seizure.

541
01:48:33,000 --> 01:48:35,000
That's a good idea.

542
01:48:35,000 --> 01:48:47,000
And I called for help, I called the desk, and asked for an ambulance, because I didn't know what I was seeing at that time.

543
01:48:47,000 --> 01:48:54,000
And when the first ambulance came, they saw she was black and they wouldn't take her.

544
01:48:54,000 --> 01:49:03,000
So I was really upset then, because I didn't know what, and she was, she was, her seizure lasted a long time.

545
01:49:03,000 --> 01:49:13,000
And so I called John, who was in another room, and I said, I can't get an ambulance, you have to help me get somebody to take to the hospital.

546
01:49:13,000 --> 01:49:26,000
And so finally we got an ambulance, and we went to the hospital, and they treated her for about, once she, they got her conscious, and she said that she had epilepsy.

547
01:49:26,000 --> 01:49:33,000
I don't know what they did, because I wasn't in the emergency room, but they said, okay, now you go home. We went home.

548
01:49:33,000 --> 01:49:36,000
And then of course she had another seizure.

549
01:49:36,000 --> 01:49:38,000
She had another seizure.

550
01:49:38,000 --> 01:49:49,000
And so it was a hard, it was a hard lesson in how unequal, I mean I'm sure she'd been white, they would have kept her.

551
01:49:49,000 --> 01:49:52,000
It was a terrible experience. Have you ever seen a grandma seizure?

552
01:49:52,000 --> 01:49:56,000
It's unbelievable. You think somebody's dying right in front of you?

553
01:49:56,000 --> 01:50:00,000
I figured after that, we might as well get married.

554
01:50:00,000 --> 01:50:07,000
I thought, actually after I left on that trip, actually that's a personal story, inside our personal story.

555
01:50:08,000 --> 01:50:15,000
So then we went home, right? But I didn't get, John didn't get to go home. I had some vacation coming.

556
01:50:15,000 --> 01:50:19,000
At home at that time was Philadelphia, where my folks were.

557
01:50:19,000 --> 01:50:32,000
And so I took hopped the plane in Montgomery to go to Philly, and John got ordered to, you know, the guy that did Julius LeVonne Chambers to the clan?

558
01:50:32,000 --> 01:50:37,000
They'd bombed Julius LeVonne Chambers house in Charlotte.

559
01:50:37,000 --> 01:50:41,000
I think John also knew I was from Gastonia, NC next door.

560
01:50:41,000 --> 01:50:44,000
But my family was in Gastonia, NC.

561
01:50:44,000 --> 01:50:54,000
So he sent me to Charlotte to investigate. We didn't know, we actually ended up going for a grand jury.

562
01:50:54,000 --> 01:51:03,000
Because there was some clan activity in Charlotte. I mean, they were after Julius, and fortunately it wouldn't hurt.

563
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:08,000
But the same fill I was telling you about with about the Carroll County, MS case, Nicholas deB. Katzenbach? — actually probably Nick Katzenbach?.

564
01:51:08,000 --> 01:51:17,000
I don't know how it happened, but he was in Charlotte to help me do this investigation, where we ended up in front of a grand jury.

565
01:51:17,000 --> 01:51:22,000
But Nick and I, during the, we were at lunch two days later.

566
01:51:22,000 --> 01:51:29,000
And I said, Nick, we were going, standing in line to go to lunch, there was a rest of the long line.

567
01:51:29,000 --> 01:51:37,000
I said, Nick, I'm going to, I'll be back in a minute. I'm going to call Jean. I think I'm going to ask Jean to marry me.

568
01:51:37,000 --> 01:51:41,000
That was the Charlotte trip. She'd gone back to Philly and I was in Charlotte.

569
01:51:41,000 --> 01:51:46,000
My family in Gastonia, NC is just 20 miles away from Charlotte. It was kind of like going to Pikeville, KY.

570
01:51:46,000 --> 01:51:52,000
And so anyway, I called up and spoke to her and spoke to her mom and dad.

571
01:51:52,000 --> 01:51:55,000
And what next day they were on the road to Gastonia, NC.

572
01:51:55,000 --> 01:52:10,000
My family may not know everything, but they figured out really quick that marrying somebody with a German name, they better, they better present themselves before John's parents immediately so that they could say it.

573
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:14,000
They could say it, establish rapport before.

574
01:52:14,000 --> 01:52:18,000
Well, it's just a little sidebar, but that's what, that's actually what happened.

575
01:52:18,000 --> 01:52:23,000
But proposed her over the phone. We'd worked hard. I thought if she put me through this.

576
01:52:23,000 --> 01:52:27,000
No, we know what you're doing with somebody, you really get to know them. And so it wasn't a big surprise.

577
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:29,000
And the whole thing, it's like being a battle.

578
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:32,000
Yeah, probably true.

579
01:52:32,000 --> 01:52:39,000
Or in the military, you're on something. There was a lot of hard people working really hard for.

580
01:52:39,000 --> 01:52:41,000
For, you know, for.

581
01:52:41,000 --> 01:52:44,000
Principles, I believed in.

582
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:49,000
How did you keep yourself going? Was it exhausting work? How did you?

583
01:52:49,000 --> 01:52:54,000
I think it just people in the civil rights division. Everybody worked.

584
01:52:54,000 --> 01:53:01,000
Everybody from the top from John door to, to the secretaries.

585
01:53:01,000 --> 01:53:05,000
I mean, everybody did what needed to come next.

586
01:53:05,000 --> 01:53:10,000
And we did the very best we could all the time because we knew.

587
01:53:10,000 --> 01:53:16,000
It was important to do the very best you could all the time because we were, this was history.

588
01:53:16,000 --> 01:53:19,000
You knew you were living history.

589
01:53:19,000 --> 01:53:22,000
And there were some divorces along the way.

590
01:53:22,000 --> 01:53:23,000
There were hardships.

591
01:53:23,000 --> 01:53:25,000
That was very hard on the wives at home.

592
01:53:25,000 --> 01:53:27,000
Yeah, I mean, if you're responsible.

593
01:53:27,000 --> 01:53:33,000
But it was, I think you're just going up hell a lot against these judges.

594
01:53:33,000 --> 01:53:38,000
And you just knew like with the Judge W. Harold Cox, you knew that you were going to have to appeal.

595
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:43,000
And you're going to go to the next and so it was called making a record.

596
01:53:43,000 --> 01:53:49,000
You wanted to put this case together because you knew you're probably going to lose.

597
01:53:49,000 --> 01:53:54,000
So when the next court looked at it, they would say, he, this is wrong.

598
01:53:54,000 --> 01:53:55,000
Right.

599
01:53:55,000 --> 01:53:58,000
And you're going to reverse that judge.

600
01:53:58,000 --> 01:54:01,000
So you had a sense of the long haul of them.

601
01:54:01,000 --> 01:54:06,000
Well, you wanted it to come around to what you were thinking.

602
01:54:06,000 --> 01:54:08,000
It was going to be a long haul.

603
01:54:08,000 --> 01:54:17,000
And I think in that way, the, if you look at the history of the Voting Rights Act and the testimony from Kat,

604
01:54:17,000 --> 01:54:26,000
I guess Katzmacken, these other people who testified, they basically had said, this is not going to work in just one case at a time.

605
01:54:26,000 --> 01:54:31,000
We are, we are doing the best we can through the courts.

606
01:54:31,000 --> 01:54:35,000
But blacks are entitled to vote and we need to have it happen.

607
01:54:35,000 --> 01:54:36,000
Right.

608
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:40,000
And so Martin Luther King that marched all together.

609
01:54:40,000 --> 01:54:44,000
And so I think the, the cases had a real place.

610
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:47,000
I mean, it was like the first attack.

611
01:54:47,000 --> 01:54:49,000
It was the first law.

612
01:54:49,000 --> 01:54:50,000
It was a launch.

613
01:54:50,000 --> 01:54:57,000
And, and I think the division in the department, the attorney general, they deserve great credit for that.

614
01:54:57,000 --> 01:54:59,000
It's not a story everybody knows.

615
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:08,000
I mean, it didn't, the movement, I mean, the relationship might have been better, but Bob Moses knew that he could call John any hour.

616
01:55:08,000 --> 01:55:17,000
He might say, no, or he might say, we can't, I only have eight lawyers who can't send them all to LaFlora County or next door.

617
01:55:17,000 --> 01:55:22,000
They developed a relationship and I think actually a life long relationship, even afterwards.

618
01:55:22,000 --> 01:55:25,000
You know, Bob became well known for this algebra project.

619
01:55:25,000 --> 01:55:29,000
He's been become an educator and we've seen him a couple of times since then.

620
01:55:29,000 --> 01:55:37,000
And Lawrence Guyot, you know, you know, you know, some of these names and many of them we knew and saw very often.

621
01:55:37,000 --> 01:55:45,000
But I think you could see that, I mean, that was enough to keep, I mean, if you knew Fannie Lou Hamer or Mr. Eskridge,

622
01:55:45,000 --> 01:55:50,000
and she's out there chopping cotton or thinking she might lose her job or Eskridge is set all out there by himself,

623
01:55:50,000 --> 01:55:57,000
he wants just all he wants is to get his kid into school, which certainly is not the most popular thing to do.

624
01:55:57,000 --> 01:56:00,000
I mean, he's really, they're putting their lives online.

625
01:56:00,000 --> 01:56:03,000
I don't think, I never felt like we were putting our life on the line.

626
01:56:03,000 --> 01:56:10,000
I mean, I think you've got that little yellow, you've got that black thing in your pocket.

627
01:56:11,000 --> 01:56:17,000
This is one, I would just happen to see it, it was the one that has me up front.

628
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:26,000
But you know, you've got that little black thing in your pocket is the Justice Department ID, which people I think knew.

629
01:56:26,000 --> 01:56:33,000
I mean, most of these rural counties, they figured you were either an insurance salesman or you were a Justice Department lawyer.

630
01:56:33,000 --> 01:56:35,000
It goes, you're in a suit and tie.

631
01:56:36,000 --> 01:56:38,000
Yeah, I mean...

632
01:56:38,000 --> 01:56:43,000
But some of the civilized workers dressed well, too, at least, at certain point.

633
01:56:43,000 --> 01:56:47,000
Yeah, I don't think they were too conscious, but they certainly didn't look.

634
01:56:47,000 --> 01:56:54,000
I mean, they were students from all over.

635
01:56:54,000 --> 01:57:01,000
I was thinking when you just mentioned that we had this case in Itta Bena, MS, the black section in itabina,

636
01:57:01,000 --> 01:57:04,000
which is outside of Greenwood, MS, what, Leflore County, MS?

637
01:57:04,000 --> 01:57:07,000
Black section is known as Balance Do.

638
01:57:07,000 --> 01:57:09,000
Had you read it? You're shaking your head.

639
01:57:09,000 --> 01:57:14,000
I was one of those doing some research, yeah.

640
01:57:14,000 --> 01:57:21,000
I mean, they had a, they were in the church night after night, this group, and somebody threw a smoke bomb into the church.

641
01:57:21,000 --> 01:57:28,000
So they go to the deputy sheriff, they take all of the church, the whole group goes up to the deputy sheriff's house.

642
01:57:28,000 --> 01:57:31,000
It's night time.

643
01:57:31,000 --> 01:57:35,000
They arrest them from 15 to 80.

644
01:57:35,000 --> 01:57:38,000
The oldest person was 80, the youngest 15.

645
01:57:38,000 --> 01:57:40,000
They took a meant jail the next morning.

646
01:57:40,000 --> 01:57:45,000
I think it was the next morning, that maybe two days later, they tried them in groups of ten.

647
01:57:45,000 --> 01:57:47,000
What was the chart?

648
01:57:47,000 --> 01:57:49,000
They were disturbing the peace.

649
01:57:49,000 --> 01:57:51,000
Like going to the...

650
01:57:51,000 --> 01:57:53,000
Yeah, going to the church.

651
01:57:53,000 --> 01:57:56,000
And I don't have the pictures of it.

652
01:57:56,000 --> 01:57:59,000
They're finally lost it to get them out to try to...

653
01:57:59,000 --> 01:58:06,000
And they sent them all, they all find them all, I think, $500, and they sent them to 30 days in jail, the county farm.

654
01:58:06,000 --> 01:58:11,000
All of it, a few days later, they let some of the really older people out.

655
01:58:11,000 --> 01:58:18,000
The guy's name was Artie Burr, but we filed this case, and John put me on the stand to talk about,

656
01:58:18,000 --> 01:58:23,000
I sat there and watched them convict all these people, this justice of the peace.

657
01:58:23,000 --> 01:58:27,000
And so we filed that case, and actually eventually we...

658
01:58:27,000 --> 01:58:30,000
That was for Judge Clayton and we lost.

659
01:58:30,000 --> 01:58:37,000
What happened in the meantime was the National Council of Church has got some bond money, and got these people out.

660
01:58:37,000 --> 01:58:42,000
But I went up there every day to that penal farm to interview these people for about two weeks.

661
01:58:42,000 --> 01:58:46,000
But they were sitting there in terrible shape.

662
01:58:46,000 --> 01:58:47,000
For no reason at all.

663
01:58:47,000 --> 01:58:50,000
I mean, it's kind of like these things you see in other...

664
01:58:50,000 --> 01:58:54,000
Nobody was killed in that situation, but it was...

665
01:58:54,000 --> 01:59:00,000
It would never happen if you were white, if that was a white group, never in your life at that time.

666
01:59:00,000 --> 01:59:03,000
This was 63 again.

667
01:59:03,000 --> 01:59:07,000
I mean, they're just all these incidents that ended up leading up...

668
01:59:07,000 --> 01:59:12,000
I mean, at some point Congress had to do something.

669
01:59:12,000 --> 01:59:14,000
And they did.

670
01:59:14,000 --> 01:59:17,000
And Johnson, I mean, this...

671
01:59:17,000 --> 01:59:20,000
And the people who drafted that.

672
01:59:20,000 --> 01:59:22,000
So here's the...

673
01:59:22,000 --> 01:59:36,000
This was the Bogalusa, LA barber spraying water on one of the protesters who was there to help during that case.

674
01:59:36,000 --> 01:59:38,000
Were you there, Jean?

675
01:59:38,000 --> 01:59:41,000
In Bogalusa, LA?

676
01:59:41,000 --> 01:59:44,000
Yeah, you may very well have.

677
01:59:44,000 --> 01:59:47,000
It's still running as a barber shop.

678
01:59:47,000 --> 01:59:50,000
He would cut hair for blocks.

679
01:59:50,000 --> 01:59:51,000
Ray Mowray.

680
01:59:51,000 --> 01:59:54,000
Well, that poster, courage.

681
01:59:54,000 --> 01:59:56,000
Have you seen that one?

682
01:59:56,000 --> 01:59:58,000
Where they...

683
01:59:58,000 --> 02:00:00,000
That was this...

684
02:00:00,000 --> 02:00:02,000
Maybe that was Bogalusa, LA.

685
02:00:02,000 --> 02:00:04,000
I never knew.

686
02:00:04,000 --> 02:00:08,000
I haven't in the other room. That's why I know it.

687
02:00:08,000 --> 02:00:13,000
Where... I know that we're about on the anniversary.

688
02:00:13,000 --> 02:00:16,000
So I wouldn't ask about the march on Washington.

689
02:00:16,000 --> 02:00:20,000
Where were you in the field when that?

690
02:00:20,000 --> 02:00:23,000
I was in Washington during that little period.

691
02:00:23,000 --> 02:00:25,000
I was thinking about all the 63 stuff.

692
02:00:25,000 --> 02:00:33,000
I was there and I was in the Department of Justice watching the march.

693
02:00:33,000 --> 02:00:37,000
Our office was on the first floor.

694
02:00:37,000 --> 02:00:40,000
So I think I went outside and watched some of it.

695
02:00:40,000 --> 02:00:42,000
I didn't get up to the speakers.

696
02:00:42,000 --> 02:00:43,000
It was actually a work day.

697
02:00:43,000 --> 02:00:48,000
I was in Miss Hamers case.

698
02:00:48,000 --> 02:00:50,000
What was the date?

699
02:00:50,000 --> 02:00:51,000
It's now.

700
02:00:51,000 --> 02:00:53,000
What was the date of the march on Washington?

701
02:00:53,000 --> 02:00:55,000
It would have been now, right?

702
02:00:55,000 --> 02:00:56,000
Yeah, it's in a couple weeks.

703
02:00:56,000 --> 02:01:00,000
I think it was just during a little interim period that I was in Washington and saw the march.

704
02:01:00,000 --> 02:01:03,000
But it was really a work day.

705
02:01:03,000 --> 02:01:06,000
Unless you took off to be part of that.

706
02:01:06,000 --> 02:01:12,000
But I do remember the march.

707
02:01:12,000 --> 02:01:18,000
You had a role to play later on when they had the city.

708
02:01:18,000 --> 02:01:20,000
During the Washington riots.

709
02:01:20,000 --> 02:01:25,000
Right before then when they had the...

710
02:01:25,000 --> 02:01:27,000
Resurrection City?

711
02:01:27,000 --> 02:01:30,000
Oh, yeah.

712
02:01:30,000 --> 02:01:33,000
I mean, we were again.

713
02:01:33,000 --> 02:01:36,000
It was one of those observer working in between things.

714
02:01:36,000 --> 02:01:41,000
Marian Wright Edelman, who's head of the Children's Defense Fund was negotiating with John.

715
02:01:41,000 --> 02:01:43,000
How long can we stay?

716
02:01:43,000 --> 02:01:50,000
They were going to stay there and try to get some of their demands met and on voting.

717
02:01:50,000 --> 02:01:52,000
What was that the aftermath, too?

718
02:01:52,000 --> 02:01:55,000
Do you remember the Resurrection City?

719
02:01:55,000 --> 02:01:59,000
Did that follow?

720
02:01:59,000 --> 02:02:01,000
Is it Portable's campaign?

721
02:02:01,000 --> 02:02:04,000
I get these mixed up, so I'm not sure.

722
02:02:04,000 --> 02:02:07,000
I was trying to remember it seemed like it came right after something.

723
02:02:07,000 --> 02:02:09,000
But we were...

724
02:02:09,000 --> 02:02:14,000
I mean, the riots were right before,

725
02:02:14,000 --> 02:02:20,000
right after the Nixon came into office.

726
02:02:20,000 --> 02:02:23,000
The big... because John N. Mitchell...

727
02:02:23,000 --> 02:02:24,000
Well, no, there were...

728
02:02:24,000 --> 02:02:26,000
I was thinking about the riots.

729
02:02:26,000 --> 02:02:31,000
I was thinking about the inauguration I was on the street through Nixon and Mark.

730
02:02:31,000 --> 02:02:36,000
We had quite a number of people out with Mitchell.

731
02:02:36,000 --> 02:02:41,000
At that point, we weren't going to stay much really...

732
02:02:41,000 --> 02:02:47,000
Trying to ensure that that was going to be a safe process.

733
02:02:47,000 --> 02:02:49,000
During the riots...

734
02:02:49,000 --> 02:02:51,000
What's after King's assassination?

735
02:02:51,000 --> 02:02:54,000
It was after Martin Luther King was killed, right?

736
02:02:54,000 --> 02:02:56,000
1968.

737
02:02:56,000 --> 02:03:00,000
Now there...

738
02:03:00,000 --> 02:03:04,000
I worked Nicholas deB. Katzenbach? — actually probably Nick Katzenbach?, the same fellow I mentioned earlier,

739
02:03:04,000 --> 02:03:11,000
and he and I went to Memphis, and we prepared the extradition papers to get Ray, James Earl Ray,

740
02:03:11,000 --> 02:03:14,000
back to this country from England.

741
02:03:14,000 --> 02:03:17,000
So I remember getting these affidavits.

742
02:03:17,000 --> 02:03:19,000
You all just came from Memphis.

743
02:03:19,000 --> 02:03:21,000
We were just there, we just went to the museum.

744
02:03:21,000 --> 02:03:23,000
The New... so right's museum?

745
02:03:23,000 --> 02:03:24,000
Yeah.

746
02:03:24,000 --> 02:03:26,000
Yeah, it's a one that was quite impressive.

747
02:03:26,000 --> 02:03:29,000
And they added a section since we were...

748
02:03:29,000 --> 02:03:31,000
You and I went to the first one, right?

749
02:03:31,000 --> 02:03:33,000
They added a whole new section, I think, which I haven't seen yet.

750
02:03:33,000 --> 02:03:36,000
They're building a huge new wing right now, 27 million dollars.

751
02:03:36,000 --> 02:03:37,000
Really?

752
02:03:37,000 --> 02:03:41,000
But they've got all the state's evidence on display.

753
02:03:41,000 --> 02:03:42,000
Oh, really?

754
02:03:42,000 --> 02:03:45,000
I mean, this was towards the very beginning,

755
02:03:45,000 --> 02:03:50,000
so we were getting affidavits from police officers and fingerprint people.

756
02:03:50,000 --> 02:03:58,000
I'm looking at the gun and what we needed was enough information together to get him extradited back to this country.

757
02:03:58,000 --> 02:04:02,000
I think the extradition papers were really prepared in Washington by some...

758
02:04:02,000 --> 02:04:07,000
but he and I went down and we got all this information together.

759
02:04:07,000 --> 02:04:10,000
And then built to you in the Civil Rights Division?

760
02:04:10,000 --> 02:04:11,000
Interesting.

761
02:04:12,000 --> 02:04:18,000
Now, I think probably the Attorney General's office may have put the case pieces together,

762
02:04:18,000 --> 02:04:21,000
but they wanted us to do that.

763
02:04:21,000 --> 02:04:28,000
They wanted me and I don't know where we were at the time.

764
02:04:28,000 --> 02:04:30,000
Maybe in the Carroll County?

765
02:04:30,000 --> 02:04:32,000
No, it was 68.

766
02:04:32,000 --> 02:04:40,000
And then after that, I remember when these rights in Washington, Cyrus R. Vance, was my boss.

767
02:04:41,000 --> 02:04:46,000
I mean, he wasn't at the Civil Rights Division, but he was secretary of something.

768
02:04:46,000 --> 02:04:51,000
And I spent a lot of time with him for a couple of days trying to...

769
02:04:51,000 --> 02:04:56,000
they were arresting a lot of people, you know, and they were sending him to a place in...

770
02:04:56,000 --> 02:04:58,000
Marlund, Quantico?

771
02:04:58,000 --> 02:05:08,000
We were quite a little vague, but for me, some of the division was very much involved in that again.

772
02:05:08,000 --> 02:05:20,000
I think again, partly because the protesters and the black activists knew that they were going to get a fair shake.

773
02:05:20,000 --> 02:05:29,000
People were going to be respectful and appreciate what they did, but that we had a job to do.

774
02:05:29,000 --> 02:05:34,000
And Jean mentioned the poll tax case a while ago.

775
02:05:34,000 --> 02:05:38,000
I just don't know how much you want to say about that, but the...

776
02:05:38,000 --> 02:05:46,000
you know, the poll tax was another one of those reconstruction act things that required people to pay, cheer, to be able to...

777
02:05:46,000 --> 02:05:48,000
as a condition of voting.

778
02:05:48,000 --> 02:05:53,000
And then it was cumulative over time and was only throughout the South.

779
02:05:53,000 --> 02:05:58,000
It was another device to prevent people from registering to vote.

780
02:05:58,000 --> 02:06:07,000
So the legislation that implemented the Voting Rights Act, there had been one case that had been...

781
02:06:07,000 --> 02:06:25,000
I think one of the Lawyers Committee might have filed a case, but anyway, the Voting Rights Act of 1965 required the Attorney General to forthwith file an action to contest the poll tax in the Southern States.

782
02:06:25,000 --> 02:06:32,000
And we had those cases ready to go, and on the Monday, I went down on the Monday after the act was signed.

783
02:06:32,000 --> 02:06:36,000
I went to miss to Jackson and filed the poll tax case in Mississippi.

784
02:06:36,000 --> 02:06:41,000
Turned out, I ended up working and preparing the Alabama poll tax case.

785
02:06:41,000 --> 02:06:52,000
And Stephen J. Pollak, who was by then the Assistant Attorney General, was maybe his first assistant still before he became Assistant Attorney General.

786
02:06:52,000 --> 02:06:55,000
I think so. He argued the case.

787
02:06:55,000 --> 02:07:04,000
So we put all these cases together and we basically had this history of segregation, all the segregation statutes.

788
02:07:04,000 --> 02:07:08,000
The interesting thing in that Alabama case was that...

789
02:07:08,000 --> 02:07:21,000
and this is in the opinion that the court issued, just before, even after we filed this case, there was an election coming up locally, a statewide election.

790
02:07:21,000 --> 02:07:28,000
And Governor Wallace had a brochure printed with his picture on it that went...

791
02:07:28,000 --> 02:07:39,000
that the highway patrol went all over Alabama, distributing it to all the white schools to take home to their parents.

792
02:07:39,000 --> 02:07:44,000
Not only to the white schools. I mean, this is done after we filed this case.

793
02:07:44,000 --> 02:07:53,000
So we put it in the record. And if you open the opinion, you see this brochure with Wallace's picture on it describing this thing.

794
02:07:53,000 --> 02:08:05,000
Even down to the right before trial, they were going to do everything they could to prevent blacks or at least to maximize the white election and electorate.

795
02:08:05,000 --> 02:08:15,000
And so there was all this history. We had this legislative history of all these terrible remarks made by the legislators way back in 1900.

796
02:08:15,000 --> 02:08:20,000
The only reason we need to stop these blacks from voting.

797
02:08:20,000 --> 02:08:26,000
I mean, it's so... there's no hidden language. I mean, it's very emphatic.

798
02:08:26,000 --> 02:08:40,000
And then, all the way forward, describing the statistics. But then the court invalidated the poll tax in all of these states in two or three different cases.

799
02:08:40,000 --> 02:08:50,000
But it was another... and it was, again, the result of all this litigation that had come along. I mean, where we had all this information and that had come.

800
02:08:50,000 --> 02:09:05,000
But it was another big... it was a nice case that has spent a good bit of time on. And it had been a case before Judge Johnson, Fred Gray, who is a prominent black attorney and Montgomery still.

801
02:09:05,000 --> 02:09:16,000
If you have an... he's really a terrific person. He filed a case contesting one of the elections right after...

802
02:09:16,000 --> 02:09:33,000
which, I think, was really a local election. And I represented the government that Judge... what Judge Johnson started to do was in most of these civil rights cases, whether the government brought it or not, he would order the government to...

803
02:09:33,000 --> 02:09:39,000
the United States to be made a party because he wanted the civil rights division lawyers in his court.

804
02:09:39,000 --> 02:09:48,000
John or one of his representatives. So, I... this was not a case that had a particularly good outcome, but I sat there with Fred Gray probably for...

805
02:09:48,000 --> 02:09:56,000
I think this case took two or three weeks of putting on testimony about the election and the getting all the statistics in.

806
02:09:56,000 --> 02:10:08,000
And we were advising the court this best we could about what to do. And in the end, if I'm... in the end, I think all that came out of it really was...

807
02:10:08,000 --> 02:10:16,000
maybe some reforms in the way they were supposed... they would needed to carry out their election process.

808
02:10:16,000 --> 02:10:26,000
But the election itself, if the officials was not overturned, but it was Fred's in that case that he had brought, but got to know him pretty well.

809
02:10:26,000 --> 02:10:32,000
But Judge Johnson was really... you talk about a hero, you asked about the...

810
02:10:32,000 --> 02:10:43,000
And so, so we're all... all of these judges, Judge John Judge John Minor Wisdom and Judge John R. Brown and Judge Griffin B. Bell, who was from Atlanta, eventually went to the 11th Circuit.

811
02:10:43,000 --> 02:10:50,000
He was the Attorney General. He was trying to think who the other Circuit Judge judges were.

812
02:10:51,000 --> 02:10:54,000
That were on that 5th Circuit.

813
02:10:57,000 --> 02:11:09,000
I just can't remember all their names, but it's... sure was a blessing to have them on the court at the time, because so many of these district judges were southerners who were...

814
02:11:10,000 --> 02:11:24,000
who made it very difficult to litigate in front of them, and it took so much longer, or the same thing in Louisiana, except for Judge Johnson, same thing in Northern Alabama in the Birmingham District, because you had these...

815
02:11:24,000 --> 02:11:31,000
a Northern and Southern Arneastern and Western District Federal Court in each one of these states, as we have today.

816
02:11:32,000 --> 02:11:41,000
And so, putting these initial trial records together was invariably for the next court, and it was a slow process.

817
02:11:41,000 --> 02:11:55,000
But it really, in the end, it really made the record for the Voting Rights Act. I mean, it's quite a story, and that sense, Brian tells that history in his book really well, I think.

818
02:11:56,000 --> 02:12:02,000
Did you have a permanent residence during these days, or were you... I mean, it sounds like you're in the field most of the time.

819
02:12:02,000 --> 02:12:11,000
We lived in Washington. When we went to Houston, we moved to Houston for six months, because that was going to be a fairly large case.

820
02:12:11,000 --> 02:12:22,000
But in the 60s, even before Gene came, we were probably gone. John described, it's interesting in this Florida law of you note that he wrote some years ago.

821
02:12:22,000 --> 02:12:29,000
He said, he'd go outside on a Friday. You could see the briefcase was lined up outside the Civil Rights Division offices.

822
02:12:29,000 --> 02:12:34,000
And back then, people would get on the plane. They'd either go to Memphis or Birmingham or wherever they were going.

823
02:12:34,000 --> 02:12:43,000
And the airplane were the DC-3s. Remember, there were C-46s in the Air Force, or C-47s, I guess.

824
02:12:44,000 --> 02:12:52,000
And they'd take off on a Friday afternoon for two weeks, and we'd go down and usually photograph several counties,

825
02:12:52,000 --> 02:13:01,000
we would have made the arrangements to get the FBI in, and you try to photograph four or five counties.

826
02:13:01,000 --> 02:13:07,000
I also did the Jackson Heins County, that's Jackson, with photographed all those records.

827
02:13:08,000 --> 02:13:17,000
And I know they remember, they had a courthouse in Rankin, I think it's a name of the town, not only in Jackson, but you're looking at thousands and thousands of records.

828
02:13:17,000 --> 02:13:24,000
And then in some of them, in some of the larger cities like Jackson, some blacks had gotten registered to vote.

829
02:13:24,000 --> 02:13:36,000
But again, it was not carte blanche. If you knew you, or they'd have to register some, and get a little more sophisticated, then it would in the rural counties.

830
02:13:37,000 --> 02:13:46,000
But we would all have responsibilities for several of these voting cases at once, and some of them, as they came to trial,

831
02:13:46,000 --> 02:14:00,000
the first John tried many of these cases himself, and Civil Rights Division attorneys cohort tried the case, and eventually those of us, the line lawyers, grew up a little bit under this system.

832
02:14:00,000 --> 02:14:15,000
It's a very disciplined system, and in the government, you write a complaint, and you send it up to the next person who redlines it, and sends it back to you, and you gradually is, I mean, and the, yeah.

833
02:14:15,000 --> 02:14:29,000
So we learned to be pretty good lawyers under that system. I mean, I always tell people, so I think it stood me really in good stead when we came here, because I had to teach one to teach another group of lawyers how to deal with that.

834
02:14:29,000 --> 02:14:32,000
And we'll probably just take another 10 minutes or so.

835
02:14:32,000 --> 02:14:34,000
So I went close to the final.

836
02:14:34,000 --> 02:14:43,000
Oh, no, I was just thinking about when he said they really over-prepared every case, and visualized the Houston school system.

837
02:14:44,000 --> 02:15:04,000
We took, and color-coded, on maps of Houston, every single residence in the enrolled student, to show how the lines were, it was just, you just can't not imagine how labor intensive.

838
02:15:04,000 --> 02:15:08,000
That was before computers. I mean, it was just amazing.

839
02:15:08,000 --> 02:15:22,000
We would call them dot-maps. You know, blacks had, we're red, and whites were green, and we showed where the schools were, and they were busing black student packs, white schools, and white schools pass black schools.

840
02:15:22,000 --> 02:15:38,000
Houston was, and that case had gone on for many years, and Judge Ben C. Connally, we had four or five lawyers working with me, plus how many research analysts?

841
02:15:38,000 --> 02:15:51,000
It was kind of like an antitrust case, foot lockers of records, and the Houston school case going way back, and what we wanted was busing to try to remedy the effects of this panel.

842
02:15:51,000 --> 02:15:59,000
The effects of this past discrimination, and try to get some reasonable integration into the Houston school system, because the inner city black schools were pretty bad.

843
02:15:59,000 --> 02:16:11,000
They spent all their money out in suburbia. The problem, one of the problems was you had this black core, and then you had the beginnings of a donut around it, of Spanish speakers.

844
02:16:11,000 --> 02:16:27,000
And so some of the parent, and then you had white suburbia. And so how do you really fix that? Judge Ben C. Connally in the end paired up a lot of schools. Many of them were black and mixed Spanish speakers, Chicano.

845
02:16:28,000 --> 02:16:38,000
But then they appealed that, I think in the end, the court of appeals, we were gone by then, required some busing.

846
02:16:38,000 --> 02:16:48,000
But I think the best thing that happened was that the voters threw the school board out, and they threw out this lawyer on the other side, and that had happened in many places.

847
02:16:48,000 --> 02:17:04,000
This lawyer became a millionaire off the school case. I mean, he was a corporate lawyer, but they'd been resisting desegri in his school system for years, and this lawyer had made a living off that really for many years.

848
02:17:05,000 --> 02:17:17,000
And the same thing in Little Rock, I had a couple of cases in Arkansas. This big firm in downtown Little Rock, representing these school districts, these rural school districts that were still totally segregated.

849
02:17:17,000 --> 02:17:30,000
And they were, I mean, they did other work, but they were well paid to keep the system segregated. And so in Houston, they finally ditched him, and they had a whole new school board.

850
02:17:30,000 --> 02:17:38,000
And I think that over time, Houston, I mean, it's an enormous system. Now it's twice as big as it was when we were there.

851
02:17:38,000 --> 02:17:48,000
But I think they've really reformed them on their schools. But those are different. Same thing with employment cases. I mean, we haven't mentioned them.

852
02:17:48,000 --> 02:18:01,000
When we started when I became chief of the Western section, we sued the electrical workers in Las Vegas, because the union was, blacks couldn't get a job.

853
02:18:01,000 --> 02:18:11,000
You couldn't get into the apprenticeship, couldn't get into the union because you were black, which you hardly ever realized. And it's still pretty much a segregated town.

854
02:18:11,000 --> 02:18:27,000
I mean, the housing patterns, we sued the steam fitters in Los Angeles, sued the roadway express. That was James Case, roadway trucking company with my, well, they were in Birmingham, right?

855
02:18:27,000 --> 02:18:28,000
Yeah, they were in Birmingham.

856
02:18:28,000 --> 02:18:48,000
Yeah, but the division, the same thing with schools afterwards. There were a lot of schools in Indianapolis, schools in Oklahoma City as the, as the after the Civil Rights Act of 64, the division really expanded its work into other parts of the country as well.

857
02:18:48,000 --> 02:19:08,000
I mean, it was not on, it needed to happen because the all segregation didn't just happen in the South. It might have been more de facto in some areas in the larger, much more difficult to do the Chicago school case or Indianapolis.

858
02:19:08,000 --> 02:19:27,000
So let's use this as a segue then into your move out of out of the division and to hear and the work that you took on here and this idea of taking on other social justice issues and how these maybe related one to the other.

859
02:19:28,000 --> 02:19:45,000
Well, I mean, I think they are, as they are related. I mean, we hoped we could, I guess I was hoping that I could continue doing public interest work. I did talk to some private firms, but we went on this big camping trip and wasn't quite sure.

860
02:19:45,000 --> 02:19:57,000
But we left the division because the administration changed and the cases that got filed, what congressional district they were in seemed to become more important than what was in the case.

861
02:19:57,000 --> 02:20:14,000
Well, and they retreated on school, these are the issues. I mean, I think it not an easy decision and there was some civil rights division lawyer revolts. I don't know if you remember, there was some of that history when they felt that the division wasn't doing enforcing the law the way they should.

862
02:20:14,000 --> 02:20:41,000
And actually that took most of the half of my way were in Houston. So, but whether it belonged to, if you are going to leave, especially if you're in a position of some responsibility, whether they're going to fill your shoes with somebody who is not going to do the kind of work at the level that you were doing it.

863
02:20:41,000 --> 02:20:51,000
People who are really committed should you stay and fight it out and try to push him to do that or can you.

864
02:20:51,000 --> 02:21:06,000
But we decided also because I think if you stay in government service, you sort of start pricing yourself out of the mark. I mean, you're making fairly good money. You're doing fairly good economically too.

865
02:21:06,000 --> 02:21:12,000
And if you're going to switch, of course we took a big die, you know, we took our money. It's only half.

866
02:21:12,000 --> 02:21:20,000
Well, we came here, but we do, you know, we decided money wasn't all that important to us.

867
02:21:20,000 --> 02:21:24,000
Were you tired too? Did you need a break from that taste or not?

868
02:21:24,000 --> 02:21:32,000
Well, we went on this camping trip for three months with a little baby. Went to Canada and went to all the national parks.

869
02:21:32,000 --> 02:21:40,000
I mean, we sort of left in the beginning of the summer and decided then we formally didn't leave, I think, when we came back.

870
02:21:40,000 --> 02:21:49,000
But we went on a put up a tent or learned how to put up a tent in New Jersey, which we bought at a Morse end store.

871
02:21:49,000 --> 02:21:55,000
And then we went up to the state, up the coast, up the New End, up to Canada.

872
02:21:55,000 --> 02:22:02,000
We took probably a couple of months and our Michael was what, three, four, he was six months old.

873
02:22:02,000 --> 02:22:09,000
Jean was breastfeeding. And we just got away from it. And right after we left one of the firms, one we come back for an interview.

874
02:22:09,000 --> 02:22:20,000
And I said, no, we didn't want to do that. But along the way, one of our colleagues, Terry F. Lenzner, who is,

875
02:22:20,000 --> 02:22:29,000
a book is going to come out, who also was at that point, the director of legal services for the Office of Economic Opportunity for OEO.

876
02:22:29,000 --> 02:22:34,000
And they had started some legal services programs with OEO money. There wasn't a lot of that going.

877
02:22:34,000 --> 02:22:43,000
Most of those programs were in the Northeast where, at that time, under the Office of Economic Opportunity Act, you could only get a project if the governor agreed.

878
02:22:43,000 --> 02:22:55,000
You had to stay, you had to stay, you had to stay okay for whatever happened. And so there were a few legal service programs outside of the Northeast, California.

879
02:22:55,000 --> 02:23:10,000
So this, Terry had been approached by some lawyers in Charleston who once started public interest law and was public interest law firm focused on the coal issues, symptomatic issues of poverty and the coal fields.

880
02:23:10,000 --> 02:23:23,000
And so he got in touch with us and said, why don't you go down and take a look at this. I would like, I'm willing to put a little money in starting supporting this kind of work in Appalachia.

881
02:23:23,000 --> 02:23:35,000
And so we came down, we stopped and visited with folks in Charleston, and then we came down here, camped out here at Jenny Wiley State Resort Park, put the tent up.

882
02:23:35,000 --> 02:23:43,000
Jean said you better see if there any bears around. Foxes, they're wanting somebody out there but us. I mean, it was at the end of the season.

883
02:23:43,000 --> 02:23:50,000
I figured if there were animals that were eating off the campers and there were no more campers.

884
02:23:50,000 --> 02:23:56,000
So we did, we were actually on our way to Florida. It was high holidays. Jewish high where we were going to go.

885
02:23:56,000 --> 02:24:07,000
To my parents who had retired to Florida. So we came down here and we interviewed Harry, Harry M. Caudill and Whitesburg, KY who wrote, night comes to the Cumberlands and was on.

886
02:24:07,000 --> 02:24:12,000
He was on the Appalred Board and was Virginia that already started a little corporation up there.

887
02:24:12,000 --> 02:24:17,000
And just for the record Appalred stands for Appalred.

888
02:24:17,000 --> 02:24:26,000
That was the original name and several years later when we had to split the programs because of political problems.

889
02:24:26,000 --> 02:24:34,000
I mean, we weren't welcomed down here anyway. So we came here and we, the Prestonsburg, KY, we came to Prestonsburg, KY.

890
02:24:34,000 --> 02:24:39,000
We came to Charleston and talked to the folks who were there that Terry had talked with.

891
02:24:39,000 --> 02:24:46,000
And then there were, there was some lawyers who were unlicensed who were already here and then fell on him to Howard Thorkelson.

892
02:24:46,000 --> 02:24:56,000
And Howard was going to leave and they asked us to, he was going to be the deputy for Westford for Kentucky.

893
02:24:56,000 --> 02:25:19,000
Anyway, so he was leaving. So we came to Prestonsburg, KY and then drove down to Whitesburg, KY to talk to Coddle and said, we'd think about it and drove and drove on down to see my parents and the real thought was there, there are some real environmental issues, there are some poverty issues.

894
02:25:19,000 --> 02:25:28,000
There are certainly a lot of poverty and there are very few lawyers who are going to, who appear to be available to challenge these.

895
02:25:28,000 --> 02:25:43,000
Most of these private attorneys were tied up by co-companies and the issues that were described to us by Harry, this broad formed deed and the environmental issues around strip mining and coal mine health and safety, Black Long.

896
02:25:44,000 --> 02:25:58,000
And the poverty issues consumer law and there were a lot of, at that time there were a lot of basic issues around food stamps and Medicaid and the early parts of that program applicants were given a very, had a difficult time.

897
02:25:58,000 --> 02:26:10,000
Local time, just local welfare offices were very, very negative and were not very, they weren't working with the NIGG ARDO.

898
02:26:10,000 --> 02:26:14,000
Anyway, it was just, how could your dad spelling?

899
02:26:14,000 --> 02:26:15,000
Oh no.

900
02:26:15,000 --> 02:26:27,000
They were just terrible, I mean, they, they, they, you would think they were treating these applicants so badly and people were having a difficult time getting food stamps.

901
02:26:27,000 --> 02:26:29,000
Very, very much the same.

902
02:26:29,000 --> 02:26:30,000
Food family were.

903
02:26:30,000 --> 02:26:44,000
Who you got and jobs were all very political because the coal that only two industry, the largest employer invariably in these counties was the co-companies and the second largest were the school districts.

904
02:26:44,000 --> 02:26:57,000
And they were very politicized and there was much of a fiefdom as we saw in the white power structure in the, in the south.

905
02:26:57,000 --> 02:27:06,000
But I think, you know, what, what was your area that you covered?

906
02:27:06,000 --> 02:27:16,000
Well, we started, I mean, technically the organization was for the Appalachian counties in Kentucky, of which there were 42.

907
02:27:16,000 --> 02:27:25,000
We subsequently gave, gave away, we gave moved six counties into another legal services programs, the ones around Ashland.

908
02:27:25,000 --> 02:27:39,000
But the program covered these 37 counties and so when, when I first came, we had one or two, we had an office on the campus University of Kentucky when in Barbaraville and here.

909
02:27:39,000 --> 02:27:46,000
We eventually, when the Legal Services Corporation Act was passed and finally there was federal funding.

910
02:27:46,000 --> 02:27:55,000
There was a lot of controversy about the legislation to create a structure for free legal services programs, a lot of opposition.

911
02:27:55,000 --> 02:28:03,000
When we came to here, there was a lot of opposition from the local bar because they thought we were taking money away from them.

912
02:28:03,000 --> 02:28:05,000
And the community because they thought we were communist?

913
02:28:05,000 --> 02:28:07,000
Well, that too.

914
02:28:07,000 --> 02:28:23,000
Because our predecessors, they had a group of, a group of, Apple, call of activist outside agitators, call, they were Appalachian volunteers who had come here to volunteer in various poverty programs.

915
02:28:23,000 --> 02:28:30,000
And they too lived with local families and encouraged them to apply for benefits and health care.

916
02:28:30,000 --> 02:28:34,000
And hospitals at that time were turning away people didn't have any money.

917
02:28:34,000 --> 02:28:36,000
They just told me we don't do it.

918
02:28:36,000 --> 02:28:40,000
Unwent, I mean pregnant moms couldn't get a delivery.

919
02:28:40,000 --> 02:28:43,000
A lot of terrible stories.

920
02:28:43,000 --> 02:28:48,000
The situation was really pretty grim.

921
02:28:48,000 --> 02:28:49,000
So, and these...

922
02:28:49,000 --> 02:28:51,000
A little while to work your way into the...

923
02:28:51,000 --> 02:28:59,000
Well, I mean, there was a case of when Supreme Court involving the Appalachian volunteers, where I think one of the volunteers was...

924
02:28:59,000 --> 02:29:06,000
Volunteers had threatened a local official or might have even slugged him.

925
02:29:06,000 --> 02:29:07,000
I can't map them.

926
02:29:07,000 --> 02:29:09,000
No, he slugged them.

927
02:29:09,000 --> 02:29:11,000
Well, I don't know. Clark, did he hit them?

928
02:29:11,000 --> 02:29:12,000
I can't say that.

929
02:29:12,000 --> 02:29:17,000
There was a lot of controversy and they...

930
02:29:17,000 --> 02:29:21,000
And that, there was outside agitators and spades.

931
02:29:21,000 --> 02:29:26,000
And they were trying to encourage people to apply for benefits and to get...

932
02:29:26,000 --> 02:29:27,000
And that sort of thing.

933
02:29:27,000 --> 02:29:28,000
And there was...

934
02:29:28,000 --> 02:29:29,000
Health care was very...

935
02:29:29,000 --> 02:29:31,000
It was very poor.

936
02:29:31,000 --> 02:29:38,000
I mean, there were one of our friends started eventually, started a free clinic out here on Mud Creek Clinic.

937
02:29:38,000 --> 02:29:41,000
But there were all those issues that...

938
02:29:41,000 --> 02:29:47,000
If you're trying to promote social justice or environmental justice, but...

939
02:29:47,000 --> 02:29:52,000
And make the system operate a little more fairly, so that poor people have a chance.

940
02:29:52,000 --> 02:29:56,000
And then it isn't just who you are.

941
02:29:56,000 --> 02:29:57,000
And that you have...

942
02:29:57,000 --> 02:30:01,000
So often, at that level, a lawyer makes a big difference.

943
02:30:01,000 --> 02:30:04,000
Many of these people have legal issues.

944
02:30:04,000 --> 02:30:06,000
Family problems.

945
02:30:06,000 --> 02:30:07,000
Disability problems.

946
02:30:07,000 --> 02:30:09,000
I mean, disability benefits.

947
02:30:09,000 --> 02:30:11,000
Consumer law, you can't...

948
02:30:11,000 --> 02:30:13,000
How can you deal with it for closure if you don't have a lawyer?

949
02:30:13,000 --> 02:30:18,000
So your play, I'm sure, in the 43 years has been full all the time.

950
02:30:18,000 --> 02:30:20,000
I mean, especially covering such a wide area.

951
02:30:20,000 --> 02:30:21,000
Absolutely.

952
02:30:21,000 --> 02:30:23,000
Do you have a full play?

953
02:30:23,000 --> 02:30:24,000
You've been there.

954
02:30:24,000 --> 02:30:26,000
So when we were 10 off, we expanded to 10 off...

955
02:30:26,000 --> 02:30:27,000
11 offices.

956
02:30:27,000 --> 02:30:28,000
Okay.

957
02:30:28,000 --> 02:30:31,000
And this was our main administrative office.

958
02:30:31,000 --> 02:30:35,000
And then we started back when I retired in 2002.

959
02:30:35,000 --> 02:30:42,000
We said we were fortunate we started a separate nonprofit to do primarily focus on the coal issues.

960
02:30:42,000 --> 02:30:45,000
Call the Appalachian Citizens Law Center.

961
02:30:45,000 --> 02:30:49,000
But over that time, when we expanded, each of these offices

962
02:30:49,000 --> 02:30:51,000
would cover several counties.

963
02:30:51,000 --> 02:30:55,000
We were hoping we would have four lawyers, at least in every office.

964
02:30:55,000 --> 02:30:59,000
So we could do the day-to-day work and do a major, a larger case.

965
02:30:59,000 --> 02:31:01,000
We sued the state...

966
02:31:01,000 --> 02:31:03,000
Like we sued the state park system.

967
02:31:03,000 --> 02:31:05,000
Because they were discriminating against blacks.

968
02:31:05,000 --> 02:31:08,000
Still, couldn't get a job in the state park system.

969
02:31:08,000 --> 02:31:12,000
If you were black, primarily you'd end up at the bottom.

970
02:31:12,000 --> 02:31:13,000
That was familiar.

971
02:31:13,000 --> 02:31:16,000
But that takes a fair amount of resources.

972
02:31:16,000 --> 02:31:19,000
And locally and a local, a little office.

973
02:31:19,000 --> 02:31:23,000
We did a lot of those fairly major cases.

974
02:31:23,000 --> 02:31:29,000
And day-to-day divorces for people are custody matters that all of them take time.

975
02:31:29,000 --> 02:31:33,000
And no private attorney is going to do them if they're not going to pay you.

976
02:31:33,000 --> 02:31:37,000
So we have...

977
02:31:37,000 --> 02:31:43,000
What I hope to do is have a first-class law firm for poor people away.

978
02:31:43,000 --> 02:31:48,000
John Doerr wanted to put a good bunch of lawyers together for...

979
02:31:48,000 --> 02:31:50,000
to represent the government.

980
02:31:50,000 --> 02:31:53,000
So I think we did some of that.

981
02:31:53,000 --> 02:32:02,000
I think we had a wonderful terrific group of lawyers who were in fairly remote locations in small towns in eastern Kentucky.

982
02:32:02,000 --> 02:32:07,000
So you saw that as something you could do to train that next generation, the next cadre?

983
02:32:07,000 --> 02:32:10,000
I hope there was a good goal.

984
02:32:10,000 --> 02:32:13,000
I think that's what I wanted to do.

985
02:32:13,000 --> 02:32:17,000
And hopefully these folks when you are in the community.

986
02:32:17,000 --> 02:32:24,000
One of the big differences I do think is that I learned to appreciate was that we were in the south

987
02:32:24,000 --> 02:32:29,000
and spent a lot of time preparing cases, but we went home to Washington.

988
02:32:29,000 --> 02:32:37,000
When you're here and folks are in their communities, they also become part of the local community.

989
02:32:37,000 --> 02:32:41,000
So if our kids are in these schools, we care about these schools.

990
02:32:41,000 --> 02:32:44,000
And so Jean saw in a statewide advocacy school.

991
02:32:44,000 --> 02:32:49,000
Whether we've been working on education for many years, not just us, but what you want.

992
02:32:49,000 --> 02:32:53,000
You're trying to create a better community for everybody.

993
02:32:53,000 --> 02:32:56,000
And whether it's schools or the environment.

994
02:32:56,000 --> 02:33:02,000
And the environment is hard because coal miners want...

995
02:33:02,000 --> 02:33:04,000
That's their jobs.

996
02:33:04,000 --> 02:33:13,000
And when people start complaining that regulations are preventing them from mining coal,

997
02:33:13,000 --> 02:33:21,000
it makes it hard to try to demonstrate that you need regulations to protect the environment.

998
02:33:21,000 --> 02:33:23,000
And that that can be done.

999
02:33:23,000 --> 02:33:30,000
You can mine coal responsibly and comply with regulations at the same time.

1000
02:33:30,000 --> 02:33:32,000
I mean, you have to...

1001
02:33:32,000 --> 02:33:39,000
If you're going to care about these mountains, not a lot of these companies or out-of-state companies.

1002
02:33:39,000 --> 02:33:40,000
Don't care about them.

1003
02:33:40,000 --> 02:33:44,000
For many years, all the coal underground was owned primarily by out-of-state interest,

1004
02:33:44,000 --> 02:33:47,000
and they weren't paying any taxes on that.

1005
02:33:47,000 --> 02:33:49,000
So we were able to get that changed.

1006
02:33:49,000 --> 02:33:55,000
It's a strange thing about extraction industries.

1007
02:33:55,000 --> 02:33:56,000
Oh, yeah.

1008
02:33:56,000 --> 02:33:58,000
So oil is a pretty special allowance, for example.

1009
02:33:58,000 --> 02:34:00,000
Will that be taken as much as you can?

1010
02:34:00,000 --> 02:34:05,000
Then we'll pay you a bonus for all the money you've lost by having taken it out?

1011
02:34:05,000 --> 02:34:07,000
Get a little extra.

1012
02:34:07,000 --> 02:34:15,000
Well, unfortunately, Kentucky, Alaska and some of the other states had at least set up some trust funds

1013
02:34:15,000 --> 02:34:20,000
and put away some money for later on when the severance taxes...

1014
02:34:20,000 --> 02:34:22,000
They've never had the...

1015
02:34:22,000 --> 02:34:29,000
We have a severance tax here, but most of the lot of that money was spent on roads and economic development

1016
02:34:29,000 --> 02:34:31,000
that didn't really pan out.

1017
02:34:31,000 --> 02:34:34,000
So this is a very difficult period here.

1018
02:34:34,000 --> 02:34:40,000
It's not quite what we're talking about, which is there isn't coal miners are losing their jobs.

1019
02:34:40,000 --> 02:34:49,000
And no one has over time been able to demonstrate how to come up with other industries or other replacements.

1020
02:34:49,000 --> 02:34:52,000
I mean, we're at a global competition.

1021
02:34:52,000 --> 02:34:58,000
We've done things like get our little science museum started.

1022
02:34:58,000 --> 02:35:00,000
Right here, we have a nice planetarium.

1023
02:35:00,000 --> 02:35:03,000
I saw the science from that.

1024
02:35:03,000 --> 02:35:04,000
Oh, yeah.

1025
02:35:04,000 --> 02:35:06,000
We saw the science coming in.

1026
02:35:06,000 --> 02:35:07,000
It took about 10 years.

1027
02:35:07,000 --> 02:35:09,000
We have a very...

1028
02:35:09,000 --> 02:35:16,000
I mean, the history of it is really the growing up in Gastonia, NC where we now have a wonderful natural history museum.

1029
02:35:16,000 --> 02:35:20,000
That was the father, which was a scout executive I was with.

1030
02:35:20,000 --> 02:35:27,000
But so we started talking about trying to do outreach to math and science in math and science in this region in our county

1031
02:35:27,000 --> 02:35:31,000
because our scores were so low that students were doing badly.

1032
02:35:31,000 --> 02:35:33,000
So badly.

1033
02:35:33,000 --> 02:35:36,000
And I was hoping that we could get that...

1034
02:35:36,000 --> 02:35:43,000
If we get some brain power going early in math and science, we might be able to affect the future.

1035
02:35:43,000 --> 02:35:49,000
Maybe we have some smart kid who will figure out how to do a Silicon Hall or instead of a Silicon Valley.

1036
02:35:49,000 --> 02:35:51,000
So we built a very...

1037
02:35:51,000 --> 02:35:52,000
We were able...

1038
02:35:52,000 --> 02:35:57,000
Because the governor was from the next county and the speaker was from this county.

1039
02:35:57,000 --> 02:36:00,000
We politically over a couple of legislatures.

1040
02:36:00,000 --> 02:36:04,000
We got enough money together to build this very nice facility with the planetarium.

1041
02:36:04,000 --> 02:36:09,000
And a multipurpose classroom and some exhibit space and that sort of thing.

1042
02:36:09,000 --> 02:36:13,000
A really nice resource for a community this size.

1043
02:36:13,000 --> 02:36:15,000
But there are other things going on here.

1044
02:36:15,000 --> 02:36:16,000
There's a re-grossing.

1045
02:36:16,000 --> 02:36:21,000
And John was on the advisory board and I was on the advisory board for the local job course center.

1046
02:36:21,000 --> 02:36:24,000
And we just want you to know they also had a rocky start here.

1047
02:36:24,000 --> 02:36:29,000
But they were very helped by citizens involvement and stuff like that.

1048
02:36:29,000 --> 02:36:32,000
Of course, me and I think it's...

1049
02:36:32,000 --> 02:36:36,000
I'm just going to ask you if you would sing us down.

1050
02:36:36,000 --> 02:36:38,000
Sing us out with a...

1051
02:36:38,000 --> 02:36:39,000
We're done.

1052
02:36:39,000 --> 02:36:41,000
We're concluding statement.

1053
02:36:41,000 --> 02:36:43,000
Sing us down.

1054
02:36:43,000 --> 02:36:44,000
What do you think?

1055
02:36:44,000 --> 02:36:49,000
Well, we've had a very...

1056
02:36:49,000 --> 02:36:52,000
When you reflect on your life,

1057
02:36:52,000 --> 02:36:58,000
you feel very fortunate when your values are congruent with what you're doing day to day.

1058
02:36:58,000 --> 02:37:01,000
And we've been able to do that.

1059
02:37:02,000 --> 02:37:04,000
Can we thank you?

1060
02:37:04,000 --> 02:37:05,000
Ta-da.

1061
02:37:05,000 --> 02:37:07,000
Cha-ta-cha.

1062
02:37:07,000 --> 02:37:16,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

